<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Admits Mad Cow Crisis Not Over Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- British Agriculture Minister
Jack Cunningham acknowledged today that the "mad cow" crisis could
last until 2001.
</P>
<P>
He said the end was not yet in sight to the saga of BSE (Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy), or mad cow disease, which helped
undermine the past Conservative government and raised widespread
fears about the safety of everyday foods.
</P>
<P>
"The way to finally get rid of these problems and bring lasting
support to the beef industry is to eradicate BSE from the national
herd altogether. We're doing everything we can to bring that about
as quickly as possible," said Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
Although he insisted on the safety of the beef meat, the
minister added, "We're likely to get down to very low levels of
the incidence of BSE in a couple of years time and to eradicate it
altogether by about 2001."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Cunningham proposed a ban on unboned beef
following scientific advice that mad cow disease could
theoretically be transmitted through beef bones.
</P>
<P>
But the announcement sparked off protests against imports of
cheap beef from Ireland overnight from Wales to Scotland and
England. Some 700 farmers mounted blockades of the Scottish ports
of Stranraer and Cairnryan, turning back about 20 truck loads of
Irish beef.
</P>
<P>
The government said today the protests were "totally
unacceptable" and threatened tough action against farmers
blockading British ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
