<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt: Resettle Unproductive Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Lands and Agriculture Minister
Kumbirai Kangai today dismissed claims that the government
recently designated some of the most highly utilized and
productive farms in Zimbabwe for resettlement purposes.
</P>
<P>
Kangai, who is attending the ruling Zanu (PF) annual
conference in Mutare of east Zimbabwe, told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that the farms designated were either derelict,
under-utilized, were under multiple ownership or were adjacent to
communal people.
</P>
<P>
But the Commercial Farmers Union claimed that some of the
1,480 farms which the government plans to be used for
resettlement are productive farmland.
</P>
<P>
"I can assure you all the farms we have indicated we want to
compulsorily acquire fall in one of these categories," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said the government's stance on acquiring land to
redress the land ownership imbalance between white and black
Zimbabweans was receiving international support.
</P>
<P>
He described as wrong the assertion in some quarters that
Zimbabwe's agriculture would collapse should the government go
ahead to acquire the farms.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, was determined to ensure the land
allocated to resettled farmers remained productive.
</P>
<P>
"The land would remain productive because we will allocate it
to indigenous farmers who will make it even more productive," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also denied the listing of farms for compulsory acquisition
ahead of the conference was meant to please the party's
membership which was complaining about the government's failure
to implement some of the resolutions made at last year's
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
