<HEADLINE> Britain, US Warn Baghdad Over Arms Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The British and United States
governments warned the Iraqi government today they would not rule
out military option if Baghdad tried to restrict United Nations
arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after talks with U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen, British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said, "The clear message for this country and indeed for
the whole world is that this crisis is not over."
</P>
<P>
Robertson made the statement after the Iraqi government
restricted U.N. arms inspectors from visiting certain presidential
palaces and other facilities in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The British defense secretary stressed that the British
aircraft carrier Invincible, which is paying a port call in
Barcelona, Spain, would be sent to the Gulf to join the American
forces in the region if necessary.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Cohen said, "We are hoping it would not
become necessary, but we would not rule out any military action."
</P>
</TEXT>
