<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Stock Index Nosedived </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe stock market, the
second largest in Africa, fell a massive 358 points to close at
8,025 today as a cloud of uncertainty continued to hang over the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attributed the fall in the key industrial index
to a negative sentiment triggered by inflationary pressures such
as the recent hike of taxes by the government.
</P>
<P>
The government heightened the taxes because it has been under
siege from former freedom fighters to raise four billion
Zimbabwean Dollars (about 300 million U.S. Dollars) for their
gratuities and pensions.
</P>
<P>
The designation of some commercial farms for resettling
landless peasants has also unnerved investors who are staying on
the sidelines to watch events in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The mining index also tumbled when it fell by 69 points on the
back of losses in coal mining giant Wankie and gold producer
Bindura. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
