<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Swaziland, Zimbabwe Record Trade Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, Swaziland
and Zimbabwe are among only 20 countries that have recorded
significant growth of trade union membership, the International
Labor Organization (ILO) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1997/98 world labor report, Francois Eyraud,
the ILO's chief of the personnel planning and career development
branch, said South Africa's trade union membership had gone up by
126 percent while that of Swaziland had increased tenfold.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the three Southern African countries' union
membership were in sharp contrast to the general decrease in the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Sahara Africa has a total of 10.03 million registered
union members.
</P>
<P>
Eyraud attributed South Africa's gains to its high level of
industrialization and the crucial role workers played during the
country's struggle for independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
