<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial: Developing Overall Friendly Cooperative Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang's extensive contacts with personages from various circles
in Canada and Mexico during his visit helped enhance mutual
understanding and friendship between China and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
World media said Jiang's diplomacy showed that he is a learned,
wise, amiable and charming leader, who represented the image of
the new-generation of the Chinese leadership with great vision and
the determination to create a better future and orient toward the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Jiang and top leaders of Canada and Mexico
had an in-depth exchange of views and reached an extensive
consensus on bilateral relationship and international issues.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to establish a 21st-century-oriented
China-Canadian and China-Mexican relations.
</P>
<P>
In his speeches made in the two countries, Jiang introduced the
great achievement the Communist Party of China made at its 15th
National Congress and the blueprint the Chinese government has
drafted for the coming new century.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China will pursue an independent foreign
policy of peace and self-reliance and expand cooperation with
other countries on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Canada is the first Northern American country to establish
diplomatic relations with China. During the past 27 years, the two
countries have maintained and developed their friendly cooperation
on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-Existence.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Canadian Governor-General Romeo Leblanc and
Prime Minister Jean Chretien, Jiang said China and Canada should
set an example of cooperation among countries of different
cultures, social systems and levels of development.
</P>
</TEXT>
