<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Registers Best Productivity Increase in Nearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The US workforce recorded
the best productivity increase in nearly five years over the
second quarter and the corresponding quarter of last year, the
Labor Department said here today.
</P>
<P>
Non-farm business productivity, which is output per hour
worked, grew at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4.1 percent
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
That was revised down from an estimate of 4.5 percent last
month. Still, it was the largest gain since the final three months
of 1992.
</P>
<P>
Productivity increased a healthy 2.4 percent in the second
quarter and a more moderate 1.4 percent in the first.
</P>
<P>
The department said labor costs per unit of output, a key
ingredient in price pressures, fell 0.2 percent at an annual rate
after rising at a 0.9 percent rate in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Rapid productivity increases of nearly 3 percent a year
supported the post-World War II economic growth from 1947 through
1973. Since 1990, US productivity has averaged only about 1.2
percent a year. The latest productivity gain was led by a 9.3
percent increase in manufacturing, the highest in 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
