<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Urges Britain to End Ports Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern today called on the British government to put an immediate
end to a British ports blockade that has hit Ireland's meat
exports.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, British farmers have blocked the
country's western ports to prevent cheap Irish meat imports from
coming into Britain.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Irish parliament early today, Prime Minister
Ahern was quoted by press reports from Dublin as saying that he
would talk to his British counterpart, Tony Blair, urging "the
movement of goods (to) be allowed."
</P>
<P>
Ahern noted that it was the British government's duty to uphold
free movement of goods. "That is not happening. Movement is being
impeded," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently what happened is that the police have stood back
and allowed the protesters to interview the truckers and take
their action," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Irish Road Haulage Association said
companies faced "serious mounting financial losses" as a result of
the British farmers' protests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
