<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland on Track to Qualify for Euro: McCreevy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Ireland will meet the debt
requirements for membership of the European single currency by
2000, Irish Finance Minister Charlie McCreevy has said.
</P>
<P>
A report from Dublin today quoted McCreevy as saying,
"Ireland's debt to gross domestic product ratio would fall from 67
percent in 1997 to 57 percent by 2000, against the 60 percent
limit set by the European Union's Maastricht treaty."
</P>
<P>
McCreevy told parliament Wednesday that his aim was to control
public spending and correct tax inequities, striking a balance
between "proper rectitude and punitive rigor."
</P>
<P>
With the European Commission set to decide who qualified for
the euro on the basis of 1997-98 budget figures, Ireland was well
set to reach the target.
</P>
<P>
The budget would be in surplus next year, at 0.3 of GDP in
1997-1998, 0.6 percent in 1998-1999 and 1.3 percent in 1999-2000,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Irish government expects to borrow 89 million Irish pounds
(130.83 million US dollars) to meet its spending shortfall,
eliminating exchequer borrowing by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Current spending will rise by 3.7 percent in 1997-1998,
including a 517 million Irish pound (760 million US dollar) tax
and allowance package, which will take 15,000 people out of the
tax net, McCreevy said.
</P>
<P>
By tightening up on tax shelters enjoyed by the rich, and tax
allowance schemes, McCreevy projected savings of up to 20 million
Irish pounds (29.4 million US dollars) a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
