<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan: Top Donor to Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan led the top five
bilateral donors to Tanzania last year, reported the "Daily News"
today.
</P>
<P>
The other donors in diminishing order were Denmark, Sweden,
Norway and the Netherlands, according to the annual development
cooperation report released Wednesday by the UNDP country office
in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the UNDP Deputy Resident
Representative, Simon Nhongo, shows that the World Bank was the
largest multilateral donor, followed by the European Union (EU),
International Monetary Fund (IMF), African Development Bank (ADB)
and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Nhongo said total external assistance to Tanzania topped 906.4
million U.S. Dollars, which was 11.4 percent higher than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
He said 65.5 percent of the assistance given in the year under
review was in a form of grants.
</P>
<P>
The figures represent total per capital external assistance in
the year of 31.16 US Dollars compared with 28.8 Dollars in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
During the year, he said, bilateral donor agencies were the
major source of external assistance, accounting for 53.1 percent
of total assistance.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral funding agencies, consisting of the United
Nations and non-U.N. system were the second major source of
assistance, accounting for 44.4 percent of total assistance.
</P>
<P>
Nhongo said contributions from non-U.N. multilateral agencies
constituted 13.7 percent of total aid flows with the EU
constituting the largest share of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The top sectors which received assistance in the year were
transport (14.7 percent) and public administration (12.3
percent), while the export trade and disaster management sectors
received the least assistance of 0.5 percent and 0.02 percent
respectively, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
