<HEADLINE> European Shares Up, London Regains 5,000-Point Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all surged today and ended higher, with London rising to a
six-week high and regaining the 5,000-point level, boosted by Wall
Street's opening gains and the dollar's strength.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index ended more than 100 points higher at
5,082.3, up 111.6 points, buoyed by the Bank of England's decision
to keep official interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The City had largely discounted the thought of another rate
hike before Christmas but traders were still relieved at the news.
</P>
<P>
A strong performance on Wall Street and firmer futures helped
sentiment. Reuters soared after announcing that it planned to
return 1.5 billion pounds (2.5 billion US dollars) to investors.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended 1.39 percent higher on the
back of pre-Christmas bargain hunting. The DAX-30 index rose 56.91
points to end at 4,139.80.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank decided to leave key interest rates unchanged,
as expected. Meanwhile, Veba shares jumped in active trade on
restructuring news.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index ended 12.10 points up at 2,914.45.
</P>
<P>
News of the planned listing of GEC-Alsthom and a bullish
economic outlook helped stocks. The Bank of France said it was
leaving its intervention rate unchanged at 3.30 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
