<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stronger Commitments From Many Countries Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- As the World Trade Organization
(WTO) financial services negotiations draw to a close, the
Financial Leaders Group (FLG) has urged all parties to quickly
table new and improved offers needed to successfully conclude the
talks.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the case for financial services liberalization is
widely accepted, and the time for commitment to liberalization is
now," said Andrew Buxton, chairman of Barclays PLC, and Ken
Whipple, president of Ford Financial Services Group, who co-chair
the FLG.
</P>
<P>
"Several countries have made significant and commendable
progress in improving their offers; however, we need to get more
good, new offers on the table to come to a successful conclusion,"
they added.
</P>
<P>
The FLG group was formed in 1996 to provide private-sector
input and assistance to governments and all parties in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
FLG members believe strongly that commitments to open,
transparent financial markets will contribute significantly to
worldwide economic growth, as well as advance the stabilization
of Asia's financial markets and help restore investor confidence
in those markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
