<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Tries to Stop Israel's Nationwide Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Before leaving for Europe,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu today made efforts to
stop the nationwide strike launched by the Trade Union Wednesday
in protest against government's plans for wages reform and
privatization.
</P>
<P>
At the Ben Gurion Airport in Tel-Aviv, Netanyahu held talks
with Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman and Trade Union Chairman Amir
Peretz in a bid to eliminate their differences over economic
reform plans.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has said that the strike gives the Israeli economy
a bad name and that it harms millions of citizens. He called on
the strikers to return to work, saying that "I don't know what
they're striking for. It's a political strike. There is not
reason for it."
</P>
<P>
Following today's meeting, Peretz said that he hopes he and
Neeman will bridge their differences in a short time, adding
that the workers will return to their jobs as he has given the
order.
</P>
<P>
Neeman said that he was ready to renew negotiations with
Peretz. But he stressed that he opposed contempt of the law by
the Trade Union, which ignored the National Labor Court ruling
ordering workers to return to their jobs by 6 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein also called on
the Trade Union to honor the court decision, saying that the
defiance of the court order could push the nation into total
anarchy.
</P>
<P>
Everyday life was definitely disrupted today as the general
strike entered its second day, which paralyzed the country by
shutting down airports, seaports, banks, the Tel Aviv Stock
Exchange, government offices and state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturers Association estimated the strike's daily
cost at 53 million shekels (about 15 million U.S. dollars). Dan
Propper, head of the association, warned that if the strike
continued, foreign investors could be affected.
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the words of Neeman Monday,
describing the striking workers as "exploding bombs" and enemies
from within.
</P>
<P>
In response to the assault, Peretz declared the strike
Tuesday at an emergency gathering of thousands of union members
in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in a Trade Union battle
against government economic reform plans, which have sparked
fears that worker's rights would be harmed.
</P>
<P>
Some 150,000 clerks and municipal workers launched a two-day
strike last Sudday against cost-cutting measures taken by local
authorities and they resumed work only after the National Labor
Court issued a back-to-work order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
