<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Gold Conference Ends in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The three-day international
conference on Nazi gold ended in London this afternoon with its
Chairman Lord Mackay calling it "a memorable and most stimulating
conference."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the final press conference, Lord Mackay said that
some 240 delegates from 41 countries and six non-government
organizations have "made extremely useful discussion" on the
origins and fate of the Nazi gold.
</P>
<P>
"Discussion was throughout free, frank and productive. The
atmosphere in our meetings was not one of recrimination for past
events, but one of constructive examination of present actions and
future plans," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day conference, British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook announced the establishment of a special fund to
compensate survivors of the Holocaust that occurred during World
War II and pledged that Britain would contribute 1 million pounds
(about 1.7 million U.S. dollars) to the fund.
</P>
<P>
The United States government promised to contribute an
immediate 4 million dollars to the fund and would increase the
total volume to 25 million pounds over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Argentina, Austria, Croatia, Greece, and
Luxembourg expressed their desire to make some contributions.
</P>
<P>
All the delegates urged international research on Nazi gold to
be pursued further in an effort to bring full light upon the past
events.
</P>
<P>
The United States delegation announced today that a further
conference would be held in Washington next year to look further
at other assets other than gold.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizensat said at a press
briefing, "The U.S. Holocaust Museum has indicated a willingness
to host such a conference to follow up our work here and to give
these issues and other remaining questions the attention and depth
of study they so richly deserve."
</P>
<P>
"We hope to convene such a conference in Washington in late
spring or early summer under the sponsorship of the U.S. Holocaust
Museum," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the conference is far from resolving all the
outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States have called on all the 15
countries, which claimed the remaining 5.5 tons of Nazi gold, to
hand over their shares of the gold to the special fund for
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the 15 countries refused to waive their rights
to the remaining gold and hand over them to the New York-based
fund.
</P>
<P>
The conference was also marked by arguments over whether the
Allies gave the European central banks gold that they knew had
been stolen from individuals and whether the Tripartite Gold
Commission, run by Britain, France and the United States, should
open its archives to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
