<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Scores Flawed Victory over DPR Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion China
conceded its first goal in two years in the regional tournament
when it savored its opener 3-1 win over DPR Korea at the 11th
Asian Women's Soccer Championship here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Korean striker Kim Kun Sil swung in her header in the 83rd
minute, putting an end to the remarkable tournament record of
shutout victories registered by the Chinese women who kept their
nets intact without conceding any goal en rout to their triumph at
the last edition two years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, it took only three minutes for the hot favourites to
stamp their authority on the championship which they have won five
times in a row as veteran striker Liu Ailing fired in a
left-footed shot off the brink of the box.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese eleven were in no mood to cherish the early 1-0
cushion, geared up their attacks by pressing forward and found the
net again on a 17th-minute header from defender Fan Yunjie.
</P>
<P>
The Koreans, who have been described as unpredictable for their
absence from the international stage for more than one year,
played the first half with a few attempts.
</P>
<P>
With the best runners-up joining three group winners in the
semi-finals, the Koreans wouldn't give up any slip of hope and
their stamina and strong physique eventually were paid off in the
83rd minute.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side, cheered up by a 4,000-strong crowd, sealed
the victory in the dying minute as Liu struck her second with a
powerful central shot two minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yuanan, head coach of the Chinese team, said the conceded
goal didn't come as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
"I never take any opponent for granted and expected every
possible result against the Koreans, either win or draw, and even
loss." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
