<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, December 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- Coryo Securities Corp., a major South Korean brokerage
house, was declared insolvent today as it failed to honor maturing
notes.
</P>
<P>
The firm, with 1,100 employees in 53 domestic branches and
overseas incorporated companies in New York, London and Hong Kong,
was the first case of bankruptcy involved in the current monetary
crisis in the South Korean financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Because of the failure to settle the notes, the business of
Coryo will be suspended as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Ministry of Finance and Economy said Coryo's
bankruptcy means the beginning of the restructuring in the
financial sector, following an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund to bailout the sector.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan will hold the presidential election on
December 31, Acting Chief Election Commissioner Justice Mukhtar
Ahmed Junejo announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Nomination papers from the prospective presidential candidates
will be received on December 16, Mukhtar announced the election
schedule two days after the resignation by Farooq Leghari as the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
President Leghari resigned on Tuesday after refusing to sign a
reference against Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah who had been
locked in a constitutional confrontation with the government led
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Senate Chairman Wasim Sajjad has been appointed as the acting
president following Leghari's stepping down.
</P>
<P>
Under Pakistan's Constitution, election for the head of state
is required to be held within 30 days after the vacancy of the
post.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Customs authorities at the Duesseldorf airport of
Germany announced today that they have seized 130 kilograms of
cocaine on board a passenger plane arriving from Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest amount of cocaine ever seized at a German
airport, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine, wrapped like Christmas gifts and having a black
market value of about 20 million German marks (11.3 million
U.S. dollars), was found in two metal boxes with the appearance
like diplomatic luggage.
</P>
<P>
A 35-year-old Chad national who arrived on a different flight
from Spain had been arrested in connection with the drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC) failed to lay charges against former state
President P W Botha todya owing to a defective subpoena served
last month, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Botha has disobeyed the subpoena to testify before the TRC
today about the activities of the former National Party
government's State Security Council (SSC), which he chaired at the
height of the apartheid conflict.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn announced after a
meeting with TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu that although the subpoena
told Botha what date and place he had to appear before the
commission, it neglected to mention a time.
</P>
<P>
This made the document legally defective, Kahn told Tutu and
his deputy, Alex Boraine, who walked to Kahn's office from the TRC
headquarters at about 11 a.m. (0900 GMT) to lay charges against
Botha for his failure to appear at today's hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
