<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Opener over DPR Korea in Asian Women's Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Veteran striker Liu Ailing
struck twice at either side of the pitch to pace defending
champion China for a 3-1 opener victory against DPR Korea at the
11th Asian Women's Soccer Championship here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a lop-sided match, the home side attained its supremacy for
the most time, while the Koreans converted the rare chance in the
83rd minute as striker Kim Kun Sil headed in a superb far corner
from a pass off defender Pak Jong Ae.
</P>
<P>
It marked the first goal conceded by China in the regional
tournament in two years as the Chinese women rounded off the last
tournament by scooping up 46 goals and never letting in one goal.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old Liu fired the odds-on favourites for a 1-0 lead
only three minutes into the match before China doubled the Korean
deficit 14 minutes later on a header from defender Fan Yunjie.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side sealed the victory in the dying minute as Liu
struck again with a powerful central shot two minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
In today's other matches, Japan went through an Asian cup goal
feast as it crushed Guam 21-0 while India blanked Hong Kong, China
3-0 in group A.
</P>
<P>
In group B, Uzbekistan edged the Philippines 2-1 and Chinese
Taipei nipped South Korea 1-0 in Group C with a goal four minutes
from time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
