<HEADLINE> EU to Support Russia's Reforms via Technical Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is
launching two high-level policy advice projects worth 6 million
ECUs (6.7 million U.S. dollars) to support Russia's reforms.
</P>
<P>
The assistance program, announced here today by the European
Commission, will be directed at strengthening the building up of a
state of law by supporting local institutions involved in legal
reforms and at providing the Russian administration with
high-level economic policy advice.
</P>
<P>
The two projects are part of a 1996 Tacis action program for
the Russian Federation and were both signed late last month by the
commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation union. Tacis is
an EU technical assistance program.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991 the Tacis program has committed more than 1,000
million ECUs to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The building of a state of law has been identified by both the
EU and Russia as a high priority in Russia's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
It includes the training and re-training of legal
professionals, teachers and officials, and the development of
curricula and training materials.
</P>
<P>
Specified reform areas which will be addressed by the project
are company law, improvement of administrative rules affecting
business law and the civil and penal codes.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has, since 1995, financed the
establishment and operation of the Russian-European Center for
Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
Directly linked to the office of the Russian prime minister,
the policy center provides high-level advice in the economic area
to the Russian government, the parliament and the presidential
administration as well as creates strong links with similar
research and policy advice institutions in the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
