<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges to Show Strong Leadership in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair has pledged that Britain would show strong leadership in
Europe when it takes over the presidency of the European Union
(EU) early next year.
</P>
<P>
Launching a new logo of 15 stars of the EU at London's Waterloo
station, Blair said that he would take the country's coming
presidency as a test for both Britain and Europe.
</P>
<P>
"A test for Britain to show that we can and do offer strong
leadership in Europe. A test for Europe to show that it can
embrace the need for change and reform," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose Labor party won a landslide election victory in
May, noted he wanted to seize the opportunity "to show the modern,
vibrant, dynamic new Britain to the wider world."
</P>
<P>
On the single European currency, due to be launched in 1999,
Blair reaffirmed Britain's commitment to ensure a successful start
for Europe's single currency, even though his government has ruled
out joining in the first wave of the European Monetary Union
(EMU).
</P>
<P>
"It is in all our interests that monetary union work. We will
play our part to ensure that it does," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair also promised that the British government would also seek
to give the EU enlargement talks "a flying start," strive for EU
internal reform and step up efforts to fight against crimes and
environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
