<HEADLINE> Russia's Duma Adopts 1998 Federal Budget Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma (lower
house of parliament) today approved a draft for the 1998 federal
budget in the first reading by 231 to 136 votes with six
abstentions, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Duma approved the main parameters of the budget in
redenominated rubles, setting spending at 499.9 billion rubles (83
billion U.S. dollars), revenues at 367.5 billion rubles (61
billion dollars) and a deficit of 132.4 billion rubles (22 billion
dollars), or 4.7 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP), the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
At today's plenary session of the Duma, the budget was rejected
by the Yabloko parliamentary faction, but won support from the
"Our Home is Russia" (NDR) bloc.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin attended the Duma's meeting before the
vote and called on the deputies to pass the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The document is anxiously awaited by the provinces and is
crucial in order to maintain political stability in the country,
the president said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin today also urged the State
Duma to pass the budget, saying it is the most realistic budget
worked out by the government and parliament in five years of
reform.
</P>
<P>
The NDR expressed its belief that the State Duma has no other
alternative but to approve the budget in the first reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
