<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Securities Firm Goes Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Coryo Securities Corp., a major
South Korean brokerage house, was declared insolvent today as it
failed to honor maturing notes.
</P>
<P>
The firm, with 1,100 employees in 53 domestic branches and
overseas incorporated companies in New York, London and Hong Kong,
was the first case of bankruptcy involved in the current monetary
crisis in the South Korean financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Because of the failure to settle the notes, the business of
Coryo will be suspended as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A business source said the dishonored promissory notes totaled
17 billion won (about 14.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Coryo, founded in 1959 and listed in 1986, with 10 affiliated
firms covering investment and management, life insurance, trade,
pharmaceuticals and other areas, was one of the nine
financially-troubled firms forbidden to conduct foreign currency
business last week.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Ministry of Finance and Economy said Coryo's
bankruptcy means the beginning of the restructuring in the
financial sector, following an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund to bailout the sector.
</P>
<P>
While ministry officials said there will be no more bankruptcy
in the financial sector, industry experts predict that it is
possible that two or three other ailing securities firms may
become insolvent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
