<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Annual Inflation Falls to 1.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's annual
rate of inflation fell to 1.7 percent in October from 1.8 percent
in September, Eurostat reported today.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of inflation a year earlier was 2.3 percent,
according to the Luxembourg-based statistical agency of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Lowest inflation rates were registered in Ireland with 0.8
percent and France and Austria both at 1.1 percent. Five other
member states were also below the EU average.
</P>
<P>
Greece posted the highest inflation rate at 4.6 percent,
followed by Sweden at 2.7 percent and the Netherlands at 2.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The annual inflation rate in the European Economic Area, which
also includes Norway and Iceland, was also 1.7 percent. Norway
had an inflation rate of 1.9 percent, while Iceland reported 2.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The figure was calculated as an average of the harmonized
indices of consumer prices of EU member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
