<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Allows Private Firms to Buy Tea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye has allowed private companies to buy tea leaves
from farmers in Rungwe District, Mbeya Region in the southwest,
after the Tanzania Tea Authority (TTA) failed to pay farmers.
</P>
<P>
TTA owes the farmers a total of 84 million shillings (about
134,400 U.S. Dollars), according to "The Guardian" today.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye, who is on a six-day tour to the region, gave the green
light in Tukuyu town Thursday, after the farmers told him that
with no economic returns they have to uproot tea plants.
</P>
<P>
The Rungwe District Commissioner, Ms Cynthia Ngoye, said TTA's
payment failure has frustrated the district's efforts to mobilize
farmers to cultivate tea.
</P>
<P>
TTA production manager Juma Chiloga said TTA had planned to
pay the farmers in three phases, but the plans failed because the
money allocated, totalling 32 million shillings, was not
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
The Premier said he has made such a decision to encourage
farmers to boost the production of tea which is one of the major
foreign exchange earners of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
