<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Edges Down in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The jobless rate in Canada edged
down to 9.0 percent in November from 9.1 percent in October,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
In November, employment rose by 34,000 jobs, bringing the job
creation total for the year to 302,000, the federal statistics
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Full-time employment was up 41,000 after declining slightly in
the previous month. So far this year, full-time jobs have
increased by 266,000.
</P>
<P>
November shows an increase of 23,000 jobs in health and social
services. There were also 10,000 more jobs in the agriculture
sector.
</P>
<P>
But there was little change in manufacturing employment. In
the retail sector, employment fell by 27,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
In November, the private sector continued to outperform the
public sector in job creation, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The private sector grew by 79,000 jobs to bring the total
employment gains for this year to 236,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
