<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parts Replacement On Bridge Over China's Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred builders and
technicians in Nanjing, the capital city of east China's Jiangsu
province, started a month-long parts replacement on its first
Yangtze River Bridge, today.
</P>
<P>
The parts renewal project will cost more than 14 million yuan
(1.69 million US dollars), according to Railway Ministry experts
who have been conducting tests.
</P>
<P>
The double-deck, highway-railway bridge at Nanjing, which was
built in 1968, now handles 200 trains daily as against a few dozen
at the beginning, but, as the speed of trains and their carrying
capacity increase, the bridge has some difficulty in handling them.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is expected to provide an example for parts
replacements on the Yellow River Bridge and the Huaihe River
Bridge, which are expected to be part of the rail route from
Beijing to Shanghai -- the country's first main trunk line with
seamless rails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
