<HEADLINE> Kidnapped Victims Rescued in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Combined forces of the
Philippine military, police and local government officials today
successfully rescued 12 kidnap victims who were abducted Thursday
in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The victims were rescued in Piagapo, Lanao del Sur province,
around 2:00 p.m., the Philippine News Agency today quoted
Superintendent Cosain Alonto, provincial police director, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the saved kidnap victims are mentors of the Mindanao
State University and four others remain unidentified, but reports
said they are students of the university.
</P>
<P>
Seven heavily-armed kidnappers Thursday abducted 15 people
aboard a minibus and then released three of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Alonto said the abductors were cordoned in Piagapo town and had
no place to go, which prompted them to abandon the victims.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports identified the kidnapping suspects as members
of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), a former Muslim
rebel group which signed a peace accord with the government last
year.
</P>
<P>
Demands set by the disgruntled MNLF members prior to the rescue
of the victims were replacement of 52 firearms earlier surrendered
to the government and immediate release of their overdue
livelihood funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
