<HEADLINE> South Koreans Pocket Golds in Short Track Speed Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean skaters took the
men's title and finished one-two in the women event in the opening
day of the three-day Japan Challenge Cup short track speed skating
competition on Friday in Nobeyama, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Lee Jun-Hwan, 20, ranked fifth in the world, led throughout
quarter-final, semi-final and final races in men's 1,500-meter
session, timing two minutes and 24.525 seconds.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Jiajun ranked second with 0.145 seconds behind and
Japan's Satoru Terao third with 0.152 seconds behind in the fifth
leg of the ranking series counting towards the world championships
in Nagano in March.
</P>
<P>
Won Hae-Kyung beat current world champion compatriot Chun
Lee-Kyung with a time of 2:27.066 to win women's 1,500-meter final.
</P>
<P>
Chun finished second with 0.061 seconds behind, while China's
Yang Yang took home the bronze, who shared the top spot with Chun
at the world championships, by clocked 2:27.738.
</P>
<P>
The fourth round of the series at Seoul, South Korea, was
cancelled.
</P>
<P>
Top skaters will be seeded for the world championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
