<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First CDMA Network Built in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- China has established the
first CDMA (code division multiple access) network in south
China's Guangdong Province, and will put it into commercial
operation by next summer.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by a local official at '97 Expo Comm
South China, a computer and telecommunications trade show held in
Guangzhou on December 2-5.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xuedao, vice-director of the Guangdong Posts and
Telecommunications Administration, said that the CDMA network,
which is regarded as a possible substitute to the present GSM
(global service for mobile communications) wireless system, has
begun trial operation in Guangzhou and Panyu in the province. It
is equipped with 13 base stations and has a switching capacity of
20,000.
</P>
<P>
He said that a special operator, Guangdong Great Wall Mobile
Communications Co., was launched to take charge of the CDMA
service in the province.
</P>
<P>
The province will further expand the switching capacity of the
network next year, Chen said. Lucent Technologies, one of the
leading telecommunications companies in the United States, will
continue to supply the project with its CDMA technology and
equipment, including its flagship switching machine -- the
5ESS-2000 Switch.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Guangdong, three large cities in China --
Beijing, Shanghai and Xi'an -- have also initiated CDMA projects
to improve the technical quality of their mobile communications
systems.
</P>
<P>
Representatives with Lucent Technologies (China) Co Ltd,
said at the exhibition that the Guangdong CDMA network passed the
roaming service test by the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications last September. CDMA users in the province
will be connected with Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiuchuan, vice director of the Mobile Telecommunications
Bureau under the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications, said
that the country's mobile telephone subscriptions have grown at a
rate of 120 percent over the past few years. Li said there will be
18 million clients by 2000.
</P>
<P>
To meet the ever-growing demand, "the only way out is to
develop a technology that can make more use of radio frequencies,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the CDMA technology, which boasts a switching
capacity 10 times that of the present analog mobile communications
standard, will be among the most efficient means to explore
frequency resources.
</P>
<P>
Li said that once the country opens the market to foreign CDMA
suppliers, the telecommunications administrative body will
encourage the companies to transfer their technology in China.
</P>
<P>
So far, four overseas CDMA manufacturers, namely, Lucent
Technologies and Motorola of the Unites States, Samsung of the
Republic of Korea, and Nortel of Canada, have participated in
CDMA projects in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imelda Marcos Allowed to Travel Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Supreme Court
today allowed Imelda Marcos, widow of former president Ferdinand
Marcos, to travel to the United States for a scheduled eye
operation.
</P>
<P>
With the nod, the former first lady can pursue her much sought
medical needs with her eye specialist-doctor based in Boston,
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
Imelda earlier had asked twice the country's special anti-graft
court, Sandiganbayan, for permission to travel to the U.S. for
medical help.
</P>
<P>
But both requests were denied by the court on the ground Imelda
has pending cases, prompting her to appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court laid down several conditions in granting
Imelda permit to travel to the United States, where she can stay
for only one month.
</P>
<P>
Among the conditions was an increase of her posted bail from
15,000 pesos to 100,000 pesos (2,800 U.S. dollars). Imelda was
also required to report to the Philippine consulate in New York
City and the Philippine government of her arrival.
</P>
<P>
Imelda and her children are facing a series of lawsuits before
Manila courts for various alleged offenses.
</P>
<P>
Manila courts have sentenced Imelda to 18 years in jail for
corruption and her son to a nine-year imprisonment for tax
evasion. Both cases are on appeal and the pair are free on bail.
</P>
<P>
Imelda, who was elected a member of the House of
Representatives in 1992, still faces about 100 other lawsuits for
allegedly helping her late husband plunder the country.
</P>
<P>
Ferdinand Marcos was ousted in a popular revolt in 1996 and
died in exile in Hawaii three years later. The government has
accused him of looting billions of dollars from the country during
his 20-year dictatorial rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
