<HEADLINE> Kohl Expresses "Increasing Worry" About Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has
expressed an "increasing worry" about the current deadlock in the
Middle East peace process and urged Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to further implement the Oslo and Hebron peace
accords, a German government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing about the talks between Netanyahu
and Kohl which was held Thursday evening in Bonn, German
government spokesman Peter Hausmann also said the two leaders had
agreed that "everything should be done to constructively and
resolutely restart the Middle East peace process in the spirit of
mutual trust and to the benefits of the people concerned."
</P>
<P>
Kohl also stressed that Germany and its Euorpean Union partners
would do everything possible in the future to actively support the
peace process, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who left for Paris late Thursday night, is on a
European tour mainly aimed to enlist western support for his
controversial plans for a limited withdrawal from the West Bank.
He is due to hold separate talks with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin today
and will meet French President Jacques Chirac on Saturday. 
