<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Urged to Actively Back Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The trade unions must intensify their efforts to satisfy their
workers' basic living needs and promote the re-employment of
laid-off workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The guiding ideology for China's trade union work in 1998 will
be Deng Xiaoping's Theory, the gist of the 15th Party Congress and
the basic principle of relying on the working class
wholeheartedly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the past year, he said that trade unions at all
levels have scored excellent achievements in encouraging workers
to participate in enterprise management, improve labor relations,
safeguard workers' legitimate rights and interests and help
laid-off people to find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that this year more than 600,000 management
personnel in more than 76,000 state enterprises underwent the
"democratic appraisal" by the workers' congresses, formed by
representatives of enterprise employees.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with recommendations of the workers' congresses,
more than 36,000 managers were commended, awarded or promoted,
while more than 11,400 were demoted or ousted," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, he said, more than 54 million
employees in 187,000 enterprises had signed collective labor
contracts with their employers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade unions across the country have established
some 1,300 professional institutions to train more than one
million workers each year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said trade unions have developed rapidly over recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, by the end of last June, trade unions had
been formed in 147,000 foreign-funded, private and township
enterprises employing approximately 21 million workers.  
</P>
