<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Children Study in Chinese Acrobatics School (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- At 6 every morning, Alesha and
his classmates start their day with running, jumping and
gymnastics in the China Acrobatics and Circus School.
</P>
<P>
Alesha, among 20 children from Russia's Republic of Yakut,
arrived in Beijing in October for acrobatic training. The
seven-year training program, approved by the Chinese school and
concerned organizations in Yakut in June, might turn the children
into promising acrobats, or even stars, for the northernmost
Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
"The exercises are very tiring but funny, and I've learned many
things from here," said Alesha, who is 11 years old.
</P>
<P>
Acrobatic exercises sometimes mean sweat and tears. After one
hour of morning warm-ups, the children receive skill training,
which usually lasts three hours and includes gymnastics,
calisthenics and exercises for body shaping. Another two-hour
class awaits the children.
</P>
<P>
Liang Anna, the Russian pupils' instructor, described them as
"lively, earnest and hardworking."
</P>
<P>
"But the Chinese teachers are more gentle with the Russian
pupils than their Chinese classmates, especially in the beginning
days," Liang said, "They need time to gradually adapt themselves
to life here."
</P>
<P>
Although living with amiable coaches, those children admitted
that they have cried on occasion.
</P>
<P>
"When not succeeding in difficult movements and hurting myself,
I did cry," said Alesha, regarded as the top student by his
companions.
</P>
<P>
In fact, they can take pride in their achievements. They were
chosen from more than 3,000 competitors who applied for entry to
the Chinese acrobatics school, the first and only one in China to
enroll foreign pupils. The state-sponsored school recruits only 70
trainees nationwide each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Children Study in Chinese Acrobatics School (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Besides acrobatic training, the Russian children have also been
provided with courses of Russian, Chinese, maths, music and
history of arts.
</P>
<P>
"They love studying Chinese because they want to understand the
Chinese teachers better," said Liang, claiming that they can speak
a few of everyday Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The teachers take good care of them during daily lives while
being strict with them in classrooms, the pupils said.
</P>
<P>
For the recent two months, they have visited the Great Wall,
the Summer Palace, the Palace Museum and the Tiananmen Square in
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all children spend happy life in China. Every day they
can even eat bortsch, a delicious Russian traditional soup they
favor most.
</P>
<P>
However, they feel homesick sometimes. Apart from Kosha who are
with his mother in Beijing, group leader of the 20 children, the
other pupils could only alleviate the homesickness by telephoning
family members regularly.
</P>
<P>
"I often writes back home and all of us write letters," the
8-year-old Aena said, "But I still long for the summer vacation."
</P>
<P>
The success in this field, however, is the children's highest
aspiration. Alesha wanted to choose one or two suitable acrobatic
courses after the training of basic skills.
</P>
<P>
"Our coach said that excellent pupils can also join the
nationwide performance tours of Chinese children," he said.
</P>
<P>
Valja, Kosha's mother, said, "The tradition of the Chinese
culture and quality training here will provide them good
opportunities in acrobatics."  
</P>
</TEXT>
