<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Squads Hope For Wins in World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Rated as outsiders, all the
four Asian squads are facing tough clashes with none predicting
its sure sailing into later stage of the World Cup finals in
France.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, Saudi Arabia, Japan and Iran are pitted separately
in eight first-round groups after the draw was concluded in
Marseille late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is bracketed in Group E with the Netherlands,
Belgium and Mexico, looking for its first-even win in four
consecutive outings into the finals.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, who reached the second round in the 1994 World
Cup, is drawn into a tough Group C with hosts France, South Africa
and former European champions Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Japan faces former winners Argentina, and fellow newcomers
Croatia and Jamaica in Group H, while Iran, the last team to
qualify for the finals, is in Group F against current European
champions Germany, Yugoslavia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Coach Cha Bum-kun of South Korea, the best Asian team with the
most impressive qualifiers, is pinning his hope for a victory over
Mexico as both the Netherlands and Belgium stand as hard nuts for
the next World Cup hosts.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good chance for us. Belgium and Mexico are good teams
for us to face and all of the Korean people want us to win our
first World Cup match against Mexico," said coach Cha.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, who beat Morocco and Belgium to reach the second
round of the last World Cup finals in the United States, still
secretly cherishes the hope of reaching the second round.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia Football Association president Faisal Bin Fahad
said "we are triple Asian champions and are playing in our second
successive World Cup so we are confident we can reach the last 16
- France must be favourites for our group."
</P>
<P>
Japanese coach Takeshi Okada set the target of winning a game
at the country's first World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
Iran, who booked the last berth after beating Australia on away
goals in two play-offs, remained tongue-tighted against any
prediction.
</P>
<P>
But, the Iranians also have their edge as Khodadad Azizi, the
Asian Player of the Year, Ali Daei and Karim Bagheri all play in
the Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
Iranian FA president Dariush Mostafavi said in Marseille that
"we have been waiting for this moment for 20 years. Ours is quite
a difficult group and we will have to work hard to pull off a
great World Cup."
</P>
<P>
However, British bookmakers have already had their say in the
World Cup finals wherein Iran is considered as the longest shot at
300-1, both South Korea and Saudi Arabi at 200-1 and Japan
250-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
