<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Gateway to Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The one-day regional
conference on marketing and market research closed here this
afternoon after some 250 prominent experts raised their awareness
of Hong Kong's role as a gateway to the services sector of China
and other Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conference entitled "Researching the Asian
Markets of the New Millennium," Chairman of the Market Research
Society of Hong Kong Christopher Robinson said Hong Kong is the
most highly developed services economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that many feel that Hong Kong, which returned to China
on July 1, will ultimately assume the role of China's
international financial center.
</P>
<P>
"This role as a hub or gateway into China is not just based on
Hong Kong's fortunate location as an entry point to the Pearl
River Delta. It is clearly based on the quality and
resourcefulness of our prime commodity -- people. Hong Kongers are
acknowledged to be some of the most flexible, adaptable and
successful entrepreneurs in modern business," Robinson noted.
</P>
<P>
He also listed 12 most important reasons given for the
attractiveness of Hong Kong to regional operations, including good
banking and financial facilities, top-class infrastructure, rule
of law and international business standards.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary for Trade and Industry of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region Tam Wing-pong said that Hong Kong is
an established major international trading, financial and business
center.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong remains a hub of everything -- a hub of goods, a hub
of services, a hub of money and a hub of business entities, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Into the 21st century, Hong Kong will continue its
development as a world class, high value-added service economy and
the premier services center in the region," and "chief among these
is that Hong Kong will maintain the firm hold on free trade
policy."
</P>
<P>
Describing Hong Kong's economic fundamentals as "strong," Tam
stressed that Hong Kong would play its role of a services gateway
in the region in the new millennium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
