<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three More Historical Sites in China Added to World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The ancient towns of Pingyao
and Lijiang as well as the classical gardens in Suzhou have been
added to UNESCO's list of World Cultural Heritages.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the 21st Annual Meeting of the
Protection of World Cultural and Natural Heritages being held in
Naples, Italy, according to the Chinese National Committee for the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
So far, 19 Chinese cultural and natural heritage sites have
been approved by UNESCO for the list.
</P>
<P>
Pingyao in north China's Shanxi Province was built during the
Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties. A group of
typical ancient buildings reflect the town's heritage.
</P>
<P>
Lijiang in southwest China's Yunnan province is 800 years old
and the only city where the Naxi ethnic minority reside. It is
famous for its houses and street layout.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou gardens in east China are famous for their scenic
beauty and residential architecture.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO adopted the Convention on the Protection of
World Cultural and Natural Heritages in 1972, calling for concerted
efforts to protect the common history of mankind. One-hundred
forty-six countries have signed the convention.
</P>
<P>
The World Heritage Committee, under UNESCO, each year considers
candidates for listing as World Heritage sites. The cultural and
natural sites which are of outstanding significance and universal
value, will be listed as World Heritage sites for protection by
the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
