<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Lift Sanctions on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian-American Chambers
of Commerce (NACC) has renewed its call on the United States
government to lift its sanctions on Nigeria, saying that
sanctions do not produce democracy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the first Nigerian-American trade
fair in Lagos, NACC's President Moses Ihonde said, instead of
helping the emergence of a democratic government, sanctions can
only weaken the economy.
</P>
<P>
"When the economy is weakened, democracy can not be
established nor sustained," he was quoted by local media as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
A weakened economy like that of Nigeria, he said, must be
assisted to grow and not be suppressed with sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Ihonde appealed to the U.S. to reconsider its position in
relation to Nigeria with the aim of improving commercial dealings
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also urged foreign investors not to depending on media
reports, but to look at those investors that were already on
ground to decide if the Nigerian business environment is safe or
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other western countries have been maintaining
various economic and military sanctions on Nigeria in the last
few years in the excuse of democracy and human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
