<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Cyanide Spill Causes No Injury, Contamination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Poisonous sodium cyanide
powder scattered from four barrels of the chemical in a traffic
accident in Hong Kong Thursday afternoon caused neither injuries
nor contamination.
</P>
<P>
A medium goods vehicle was traveling northward along the Tai Po
Road in Sha Tin with 32 barrels of the deadly chemical. Nineteen
barrels fell off the truck onto the road in the accident and four
were damaged, scattering some 100 kilograms of lethal powder on
the road.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred near a reservoir, but test of water
samples taken from the reservoir as precautionary measures showed
no trace of contamination by the fallen chemical.
</P>
<P>
Emergency crews were called to the spot for a massive clean-up
operation, which was completed at 3:57 AM on Friday and the
southbound and northbound lanes of the road section, closed
earlier to traffic for cleaning, had been re-opened, according to
a government statement today.
</P>
<P>
And chemical tests by a government chemist at the scene found
no cyanide compound in the air.
</P>
<P>
There was no question of normal water supply as no draw-off has
been made from the reservoir since October this year, according to
a spokesman for the Water Supplies Department.
</P>
<P>
Sodium cyanide is considered one of the deadliest chemicals.
And only a whiff would kill as the powder dissolves into highly
toxic fume when mixed with water.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong law does not require a special permit for its
transportation although the chemical must be specially packaged
and labeled, according to a Fire Services Department spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
