Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The government and the oppositions exchanged sharp words in
the debate on the new immigration law at the National Assembly
which began on Thursday. Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement accused his predecessor Jean-Louis Debre of trying to
"flatter a part of the electorate" of the extreme-right National
Front (FN), while Debre accused him of "organizing non-respect of
the law." The leader of FN Jean-Marie Le Pen has called for a
referendum on the new nationality law adopted last week by the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
-- Israel could have been cheated by its own spies. At the
heart of its secret service Mossad, a high-ranking officer had
deliberately sent false information to prevent Israel from making
peace with Syria, according to Israeli press reports. In 1996,
Israel was once on the verge of attacking Syria after receiving
disinformation that Syria was massing troops to reconquer the
Golan Heights. 
</P>
