<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Police Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today accepted the resignation of embattled Police Director
General Recaredo Sarmiento effective December 15.
</P>
<P>
Ramos announced the resignation of Sarmiento at a hastily
called press conference in the Presidential Palace late this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sarmiento, who heads the 95,000-strong national police, has
been under pressure to resign following the unabated incidents of
kidnapping for ransom in the country, particularly in Manila's
Chinatown district.
</P>
<P>
In the resignation letter which he submitted to Ramos Thursday,
Sarmiento said that in the light of "recent developments and
consistent with our time-honored principle and tradition of
command responsibility, I hereby tender my courtesy resignation."
</P>
<P>
Taking over Sarmiento's post is Police Director Santiago Alino,
concurrently the chief of the directorial staff of the Philippine
National Police.
</P>
<P>
As Ramos announced the acceptance of Sarmiento's resignation,
two suspected kidnappers were killed in a gun battle in Cubao, the
capital region, at noon today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
