<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Urged to Actively Back Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese trade union leader
today called on all trade union officials to emancipate their
minds and help workers abandon old concepts, enhance awareness of
reforms and take an active part in the country's reforms.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dinghua, vice-chairman of the 12th executive committee of
the All-China Federation of Trade Unions (ACFTU), made his remarks
in a work report to the committee's fifth session, which opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
"The goals and tasks for reforms and development set forth
during the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), convened in Beijing in September, has represented the
fundamental interests of the working class," Zhang told more than
200 members of the ACFTU executive committee.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the trade union holds that all reforms
related to the workers' direct interests must comply with economic
laws and the workers' wishes, follow the principles of democratic
decision-making and be standardized in accordance with the laws.
</P>
<P>
"We also believe that to maintain social stability the overall
bearing capacity of the workers must be taken into account and
measures be taken to guarantee the workers' basic living standards
before any major reforms are carried out," he added.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the 15th CPC National Congress has both
opened new opportunities and posed new challenges for the trade
unions.
</P>
<P>
"The deepening of economic reforms, diversity of the realizing
forms of the public ownership and the stepping-up of reforms in
state-owned enterprises would inevitably lead to more complicated
labor relations and greater pressure on employment," he
explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
