<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Committee Offers Suggestions on Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A presidential committee on
prevention of suicide has submitted a package of recommendations
to President Chandrika Kumaratunga, the Presidential Secretariat
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The committee, especially set up in March to study the issue of
suicide, has got the president's approval to implement their
recommendations, the secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The committee suggested that pesticides be restricted from easy
access to people and lethal pesticides be phased out over a period
of ten years.
</P>
<P>
A national center of suicide study will be established to
collect and analyze data related to the issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the committee asked the media to publish positive
and constructive messages which discourage suicide.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has the highest suicide rate in the world, according
to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, a total of 7,700 people committed suicides. Last year,
almost 10,000 Sri Lankans killed themselves due to various
reasons.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed that most people committed suicide because of
unemployment, dropout of school, failure in love affairs, family
problems, housing and drug-addiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
