<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher In Light Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished marginally higher in light trading today as many
investors were treading water ahead of the release of key data in
the U.S. tonight.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index rose 4.7 points to 2557.2, with gains
also held back by a poorer performance in resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
"It's a Friday. There is Christmas coming up which is taking
away some interest. And most of you have some big key numbers
coming out in the U.S. tonight and people don't want to take
strong positions ahead of that," an Ord Minnett analyst said.
</P>
<P>
The vital U.S. payroll data for November was due out tonight
Australian time, providing the latest evidence on economic growth.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a light 264.46 million shares at a value
of just 671.04 million Australian dollars (449.5 million U.S.
dollars), with rises bettering falls 510 to 487.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks fell, with the all resources index down 3.2
points to 1108.5 despite broadly better commodity prices
overnight.
</P>
<P>
Zinc miner Pasminco was one to suffer, falling 3.8 cents to 1.6
Australian dollars in trade of 7.27 million shares.
</P>
<P>
BHP also fell 12 cents, Rio Tinto and WMC improved by five
cents to 16.80 and 5.00 Australian dollars respectively, while
Woodside Petroleum was 23.1 cents better.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks suffered further as the bullion price fell to
286.85 U.S. dollars late in Sydney, from 290.25 an ounce late
Thursday. The gold index dropped 15.5 points to 866.3.
</P>
<P>
The all industrial index rose 13.9 points to 4374.8.
</P>
<P>
Telstra's installment receipts shed a cent, while News Corp
capped a good week on the rise, with the ordinary shares up 11
cents.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were mixed, with ANZ boosted by bargain hunters
after heavy selling Thursday, bouncing up 32 cents. The banks
index lifted 49.3 points to 5,374.7.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was 10 cents better, Westpac was six
cents higher while St. George shares dropped 35.8 cents as the
stock went ex-dividend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
