<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Drops Again on Gold Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A series of dips to new
four-year lows this week culminated in the Australian dollar
breaching the critical 67 U.S. cents level in offshore trading
today.
</P>
<P>
A sharp fall in the gold price pressured the local currency
down to a close of 67.25 U.S. cents, back from 67.38 late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, the Australian dollar briefly touched 66.98 U.S.
cents in New York - the lowest point since it reached 66.88 U.S.
cents in December 1993.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank foreign exchange manager Mark O'Leary said a
falling gold price was largely to blame for the currency's
weakness.
</P>
<P>
Gold's slide began Thursday after an announcement that the
Argentine central bank sold 4 million ounces of its gold reserves
in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold bullion closed at 286.85 U.S. dollars per fine
ounce, from 290.25 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the day, dealing in the Australian dollar was choppy.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig James said the
currency is likely to fall to 66 U.S. cents next week on the back
of continued flows into the U.S. dollar and declining commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
"For the Australian dollar there is not a lot of upside
potential," James said. "The Asia slowdown, which is expected to
continue into 1998, is another focus."
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen, the Australian dollar closed at 87.34
from 86.99 Thursday. It was at 1.1926 German marks, from 1.1948.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
