<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Situation in Bangladesh, Serious: Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Some sero-epidemiological surveys
carried out in Bangladesh clearly indicate that an epidemic has
already started in this South Asian country, Weekend Independent
said in its latest issue today.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the magazine said, the country is still a low
prevalence area, but this situation could rapidly change unless
preventive measures are put in place.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, more than 350,000 individuals have been screened
serologically in the country for HIV antibody both by public and
private sources.
</P>
<P>
Till the end of June 1997, a total of 84 HIV positive cases had
been reported.
</P>
<P>
But in the absence of a proper surveillance mechanism, the
magazine pointed out, this number means very little in terms of
assessing the country's actual situation.
</P>
<P>
Both WHO and UNAID reported that the number of HIV infected
persons in Bangladesh is between 20,000 and 100,000. They were
considering the risks and also analyzing the existing information
available on the reported number of cases.
</P>
<P>
In a country where 80 percent deaths occur without any
consultation of a physician, every one should be very careful in
interpreting the HIV/AIDS situation in the country, the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
Time is of the essence in the combat against the menace of AIDS
epidemic, the magazine warned. "We must act now."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
