<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Truth Commission Fails to Lay Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) failed to lay charges against former
state President P W Botha this morning owing to a defective subpoena
served last month, South African Press Association reported..
</P>
<P>
Botha has disobeyed the subpoena to testify before the TRC today
about the activities of the former National Party government's State
Security Council (SSC), which he chaired at the height of the
apartheid conflict.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn announced after a meeting
with TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu that although the subpoena told Botha
what date and place he had to appear before the commission, it
neglected to mention a time.
</P>
<P>
This made the document legally defective, Kahn told Tutu and his
deputy, Alex Boraine, who walked to Kahn's office from the TRC
headquarters at about 11 a.m. (0900 GMT) to lay charges against Botha
for his failure to appear at today's hearing.
</P>
<P>
Under the founding bill of the TRC, the Promotion of National Unity
and Reconciliation Act, a person faces fines or up to two years of
imprisonment for disobeying a TRC subpoena.
</P>
<P>
To make up, a new subpoena would be issued today, telling Botha
that he has to appear before the TRC on December 19. The new document
would be served on his lawyer, Ernst Penzhorn, as well as at Botha's
home in Wilderness near George in Western Cape province.
</P>
<P>
Botha had already refused on the grounds of bad health to obey a
TRC subpoena to appear in the first round of SSC hearings in
Johannesburg last month.
</P>
<P>
He told an Afrikaans newspaper in mid-November that he would rather
be charged than appear before the TRC. Tutu has repeatedly warned him
of criminal charges after the publication of the interview.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said he was deeply saddened by Botha's stubborn refusal to
appear at the hearing. To accommodate Botha, Tutu announced after
Botha's failure to appear at the Johannesburg hearing that the second
round would be held in George, a city very close to Botha's retirement
home in Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
Later the venue was rearranged in Cape Town after Botha publicly
indicated his refusal.
</P>
<P>
The TRC was set up to heal the wounds of the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said the intention of the hearing is not to humiliate Botha.
Boraine said: "One of the things we have to get clear in this country
is that none of us is above the law."
</P>
<P>
Botha, whose government had vehemently implemented apartheid
policies, refused to apologize for the role of his government and said
that he would not seek amnesty at the TRC, which he said was becoming
a revenge camp against Afrikaners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
