<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Send More Medical Workers to Study in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese cooperative
project will pay for 1,000 Chinese medical workers to study and
conduct research in Japan in the 1998-2007 period.
</P>
<P>
Chen Minzhang, minister of health (MOH) said today the medical
workers will be sent according to an agreement signed here today
between MOH and two Japanese organizations for the second phase of
the Sasakawa Medical Fellowship Project.
</P>
<P>
"The large-scale project has made great contributions to the
development of China's health sector," Chen said in a speech at a
meeting in the Great Hall of the People to celebrate the project's
10-year anniversary.
</P>
<P>
The fellowship was established by the Nippon Foundation of
Japan. The MOH signed an agreement with Japan's Sasakawa Memorial
Health Foundation and Japan-China Medical Association in 1986 to
launch the first phase of the project from 1987-1997.
</P>
<P>
One-thousand fellowship winners from hospitals, medical
academies and research institutions across China were divided into
10 groups to study for one year in Japan.
</P>
<P>
They made full use of what they learned abroad and became
integral to their work units after returning, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Attending today's meeting were State Councillor Peng Peiyun; Wu
Jieping, Vice-Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress; He Luli, Vice-Chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference; and representatives of the
students.
</P>
<P>
The MOH presented the China Public Health Award, the highest
honor of the country's health sector, to Sasakawa Yohei, president
of the Nippon Foundation; Okamoto Michio, chairman of the
Japan-China Medical Association; and Hinohara Shigeaki, president
of Sasakawa Memorial Health Foundation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Ready to Extend Training to Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia can provide
technical and management training to Ghana in tropical
resource-based industries to prepare for possible future
investments in that area, Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng
Yaik said here today.
</P>
<P>
Though there is a slowdown in Malaysian investment overseas
now, Malaysia could provide technical cooperation to Ghana in the
industry when the economic situation improved, he told reporters
after calling on Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings who arrived
here Thursday on a two-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
Lim said, "If things come back to normal, we can prepare
through our technical cooperation program to train researchers and
managers in the various resource-based industries that they
(Ghana) would want."
</P>
<P>
He said Rawlings, in their hour-long meeting, had invited the
Malaysian private sector to invest in developing Ghana's
resource-based industries.
</P>
<P>
Lim said Malaysia and Ghana could form part of a consortium for
ventures in tropical resource-based industries such as timber,
cocoa, rubber and palm oil where Malaysia could provide the
expertise and Ghana, the land and human resources.
</P>
<P>
A third country could then provide the market and finances for
any given project, he said, adding with the tripartite concept,
countries like France, China and Egypt, by serving as a third
country, would not only help in developing the economies of
developing countries but also in absorbing the products produced
in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian president, leading a 13-member delegation
including Foreign Minister J. V. Gbeho and Deputy Trade and
Industry Minister Dan Abodakpi, is scheduled to hold talks with
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad Saturday in Langkawi, a
resort island in northern Malaysia, where Mahathir is busy with
the ongoing Fourth Langkawi International Maritime and Aerospace
(LIMA) Exhibition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
