<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's GDP Growth for 1998 Revised to 4-5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim today revised downwards Malaysia's
projected growth for 1998 to between four and five percent from
the seven percent forecast in the 1998 Budget on October 17.
</P>
<P>
The lower GDP growth of between four and five percent is still
strong compared with the rest of the region and especially in view
of the availability of employment opportunities, Anwar, who is
also finance minister, said when announcing major measures at a
media conference here, which are expected to build up confidence
and credibility in the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the estimated growth for this year has also been
lowered to 7.5-7.7 percent from the earlier forecast 8.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also announced an 18 percent cut in 1998 government
expenditure as part of belt tightening measures to keep inflation
in check.
</P>
<P>
He said the current account deficit for 1998 was now projected
to fall to 3.0 percent of Gross National Product (GNP) from the
4.0 percent announced in the 1998 Budget.
</P>
<P>
He said that in efforts to reverse the persistent current
account deficit, lumpy imports of aircraft by Malaysia Airlines
and vessels by Malaysian International Shipping Corporation, which
significantly contribute to the nation's current account deficit,
would be rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
Applications for new public listings, rights issues and
restructuring proposals would be frozen unless absolutely
necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said banks had been advised to be careful when making margin
calls and bailouts of borrowers would be only justifiable if they
were suffering from temporary cash flow problems.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also dismissed market talk that there were plans for the
imposition of unilateral controls on currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that proposed Malaysian reverse investments, which
amounted to 7 billion ringgit (about 1.8918 billion U.S. dollars)
during the first half of 1997, would have to be deferred even if
these investmemts were to be financed through foreign borrowings.
</P>
<P>
However, investments which have significant linkages with the
domestic economy and which earn foreign exchange would continue to
be allowed, he announced.
</P>
<P>
According to the finance minister, Malaysia's current reserves
amount to 61.7 billion ringgit (about 16.6756 billion U.S.
dollars), sufficient to finance 3.7 months of retained imports.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's announcements had an immediate impact on the stock
market where the composite index (CI), which had slipped into
negative territory during the afternoon session, reversed itself
shortly after 4 p.m. today as details of the measures hit the
market.
</P>
<P>
The market barometer CI shot above the psychological 600-point
level to end the day at 607.40 points, up 31.51 points or 5.46
percent, while on the exchange market, the local currency -- the
ringgit clawed back from a new low of 3.8650 earlier in the day to
end at 3.6950 to the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
