<HEADLINE> Israeli Treasury Cuts off Talks with Strikers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Treasury has broken
off talks with the Trade Union aimed at ending a crippling
nationwide strike, which entered its third day today, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Treasury made the decision Thursday night on
the instructions of Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein, who said
there would be no negotiations with workers who were in contempt
of court.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein's orders came after the Trade Union, defying
back-to-work orders issued Wednesday and an appeal from Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, said it would continue the strike by
700,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
The State Attorney's office said that it would go back to the
National Labor Court today to get new back-to-work orders for the
strikers.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which was launched Wednesday in protest against
government plans for wages reform and privatization, has
paralyzed the country by effectively shutting down airports,
seaports, banks, the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange, government offices
and state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu called on the strikers to return to work, saying that
the strike gives the Israeli economy a bad name and harms
millions of citizens.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacturers Association estimated the strike's daily
cost at 53 million shekels (about 15 million U.S. dollars). The
association head Dan Propper warned that if the strike
continued, foreign investors could be affected.
</P>
<P>
The strike was triggered by the words of Finance Minister
Ya'acov Neeman Monday, describing the striking workers as
"exploding bombs" and enemies from within.
</P>
<P>
In response to the assault, Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz
declared the strike Tuesday night at an emergency gathering of
thousands of union members in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in the Trade Union's battle
against government's economic reform plans, which have sparked
fears that workers' rights would be harmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
