<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 More Luxor Attackers in Egypt Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Three of the six militants who
carried out the massive killings of foreign tourists last month
were college students in their early 20s from southern Egypt,
local English newspaper the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The three were found to be Assiut University students Esmat
Erian, at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, Mahmoud Mohamed
Abdul Karim, at the Faculty of Medicine, and Sayed Dessouki, a
student of the Higher Institute for Cooperatives and Agricultural
Guidance.
</P>
<P>
Assiut, 350 kilometers south of Cairo, is a stronghold of
Islamic militants who have been fighting a violent war against
Egypt's secular government since 1992 in a bid to install a
strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
The three young men were all from a village near Luxor, the
largest tourist city in southern Egypt, where they shot dead 58
foreign tourists and four Egyptians on November 17. Most of the
50,000 people in their hometown depend on tourism for a living,
said the Arabic newspaper Al Gomhuria today.
</P>
<P>
Their identities were revealed as Interior Minister Habib Al
Adly made a report on the ongoing investigations into the
massacre at a meeting between several cabinet ministers and the
ambassadors of 14 countries accredited to Cairo on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, Britain and Japan are the countries that have
lost the largest number of its citizens in the terrorist attack
in Luxor, about 500 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The six assailants, belonging to the Gamaa Islamiya, or the
Islamic Group, that claimed responsibility for the slayings, were
gunned down by police after the killings.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Wednesday, the Islamic Group said the six young
members acted independently and carried out the slayings without
orders from its leaders.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the attack, the Interior Ministry had identified
one of the assailants as Medhat Abdul Rahman Hussein, a known
militant, also from southern Egypt where Islamic militants have
been active.
</P>
<P>
The authorities gave no explanation to the delay in
identifying the attackers, but local press said this could be
because the militants had clean police records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Vaccinate More Children Against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Health
will vaccinate 60 million children four years old and younger this
month and next to prevent communicable polio.
</P>
<P>
Children in 31 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities
as well as children in transient families will be given oral polio
vaccines on Dec. 5 and Jan. 5, according to an official with the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The program will focus on children who have been given polio
vaccines less than three times after birth, especially those in
border and poverty-stricken areas, and those from the transient
population, he said.
</P>
<P>
This will be the fifth time China has launched a program
designed to stop the spread of the polio virus. Previous programs
have helped reduce the incidence of the disease.
</P>
<P>
China's long border with many countries in which polio is
widespread makes it difficult for he vaccination program to cover
all the remote areas, according to health officials. Because of
this and other factors, the polio vaccination rate of children is
declining in some areas, a major obstacle for the program in the
elimination of polio.
</P>
<P>
B. Melgard, director of the World Health Organization's
Expanding Immunization Program, delegates from other international
organizations have gone to Jilin, Xinjiang, Guangdong and Yunnan
provinces for vaccinations there. They will advise Chinese
officials on the elimination of polio.
</P>
<P>
No cases of polio have been reported for 13 years in Beijing,
where the vaccination program is carried out systematically, said
Guan Baoying, head of the epidemic prevention department of the
Beijing Municipal Health Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will provide 400,000 vaccines and set up 3,000
stations to vaccinate 120,000 children 4 and below, 80 percent of
whom are from transient families, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
