<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate Rises in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The weaker peso and higher
interest rates pushed the Philippines' inflation rate to 6. 5
percent in November, the highest since January this year, the
National Statistics Office (NSO) said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest inflation level was considerably higher than 5.7
percent for October this year and 4.5 percent for November last
year, but was very close to a forecast of 6.45 percent by local
economists.
</P>
<P>
In November, all commodity groups registered higher inflation
rates compared with October except for clothing whose inflation
rate went down to 4.2 percent from 4.3 percent, the NSO said in a
report.
</P>
<P>
The major factor contributing to the rise in inflation rate was
a sharp increase in the rate for food, beverages and tobacco,
which rose to 3.6 percent from 2.4 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
By region, the inflation rate for the capital area of Metro
Manila remained the highest at 7 percent, unchanged compared with
October.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate has been on the rise since August as a result of
the weaker Philippine peso and higher interest rates accompanying
the volatile currency.
</P>
<P>
The peso, a victim of the regional financial crisis, has fallen
nearly 33 percent against the U.S. dollar since its de facto
devaluation in July.
</P>
<P>
Despite the continuing rise in inflation rate, government
economic managers are optimistic that its inflation target of 6 to
7 percent for the year is well within reach.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for the past ten months this year stood at a
low of 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government has resisted strong calls from many militant
labor unions for a hike of the country's minimum daily wage and
banned price hikes of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
But economists predict a surging inflation rate for 1998 due to
the continuing effects of higher interest rates and the weak peso,
and a drought caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
