<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Water Resources in Qilian Mountains of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- More trees will be planted in
northwest China's Qilian Mountains in order to conserve dwindling
water resources, according to sources from the Qilian Mountains
Protection Zone.
</P>
<P>
Zone Director Xu Mingsu said that trees will be planted on
266,000 hectares of mountain sploes in the next 12 years to
increase the forest coverage in the area from the current 438,000
ha. to over 584,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Forests in the Qilian Mountains are home to numerous species of
flora and fauna, and are an important source of water for over
667,000 hectares of farmland, as well as for over four million
residents and hundreds of industrial and mining enterprises in the
the Hexi Corridor, Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Deterioration of the local natural ecological environment,
resulting from various factors such as climate changes, have caused
the forest coverage rate to fall from 22 percent in the early
1950s to only 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government established a state-level natural reserve
in the area in 1988, and has since invested over 6 million yuan
(750,000 US dollars) to build nature and forest protection stations
and research centers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the provincial government has introduced
regulations to strengthen protection efforts in the Qilian
Mountain Nature Reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0131 </DOCNO>
