<HEADLINE> African Technology Center to Be Based in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
signed an agreement with the African Center for Technology
Studies (ACTS), allowing the center be headquartered in Nairobi,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ACTS trains senior government officials across the
continent on the provisions of the Convention on Biological
Diversity.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo
Musyoka and ACTS Director John Mugabe here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The citing of ACTS in Nairobi enhances the closer
collaboration that will exist between ACTS and the government of
Kenya, especially government institutions in the field of
environment, science and technology," said Musyoka.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Kenyan government has accorded a number of
functional privileges and immunities to the body.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the Host Country Agreement will provide an
enlarged foundation for ACTS activities in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"It will provide a basis for us to forge strong links with
various government departments" as well as strengthen its policy
research and analysis, he added.
</P>
<P>
Malawi, Malta and Uganda and two international institutions --
the International Center for Research in Agro-Forestry and the
Third World Academy of Sciences -- are the founding members of
ACTS. Kenya joined the organization in June this year. 
</P>
