<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Project Yields Multiple Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A development project for
poverty relief funded by the World Bank has yielded enormous
economic, ecological and social benefits in Luliang, north China's
Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The project in Luliang, one of China's 18 most poverty-stricken
regions, is being carried out in seven counties and districts with
a total population of 1.13 million people, or some 33 percent of
the total population in the region.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has budgeted total funding of 27.12 million US
dollars for the project, with 24.19 million US dollars allocated
by the end of June, 1996. Local farmers have contributed
investments of some 29.89 million yuan (3.6 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Implementation of the project, which is designed to improve the
local ecology, has had a positive impact, with Fangshan County
witnessing record per-capita grain and edible oil outputs in
1996. The project has also helped control erosion in the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects Signing Landmine Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has announced that it
will not sign the Canada-proposed landmine ban treaty on grounds
of concerns of defending state security, local newspaper Daily
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior officers from Turkish General Staff,
who declined to be named, as saying that Turkey is still faced
with frequent attacks from rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
"Although we respect the reasons for that treaty, we have to
take measures to ensure our border security," they said.
</P>
<P>
However, the officers said that Turkey will not export
landmines in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Officials from most nations of the world recently gathered in
Ottawa, Canada to sign the historic treaty that seeks to ban the
use of anti-personnel landmines across the globe.
</P>
<P>
Some countries, such as the United States, Russia as well as
some Middle East countries, refused to put signatures on the
Ottawa treaty.
</P>
<P>
An average of 25,000 people are killed or maimed in landmine
explosions throughout the world each year, according to
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
