<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Sewage Treatment Plants To Be Built In Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province plans to set up 52 wastewater treatment plants with an
overall daily treatment capacity of 5.8 million tons before 2005.
</P>
<P>
The province will spend 11.6 billion yuan (about 1.45 billion
U.S. dollars) on the project in a bid to raise its urban sewage
treatment rate by 40 percent, according to the China Environmental
News.
</P>
<P>
The province has rapidly increased the emission of urban
wastewater because of urbanization during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.2 billion tons of sewage was produced last year, triple
that in 1987. However, its sewage treatment rate is below 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Urban sewage accounted for 60 percent of the province's total
wastewater emission in 1996, becoming a major pollution source for
its rivers. In 1987, the figure was 35.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
