<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weakening Baht May Not Lead to Export Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The loss of value of the Thai
currency, the baht, against the U.S. dollar may not increase as
much competitive edge for Thai exports as expected by some
economists and government officials, a local newspaper report said
today.
</P>
<P>
While the Thai baht has depreciated by about 60 percent against
the dollar since its floating on July 2, currencies of Thailand's
neighbors have also followed suit, blunting the much-hoped-for
increase in competitive edge of Thai exports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The currencies of Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines have
all fallen by a range of between 30 and 40 percent since July.
</P>
<P>
Although the Thai baht has depreciated more than the currencies
of Thailand's major trade competitors in Southeast Asia, the
difference will eventually narrow down, the report quoted Viroj
Amatakulchai, chairman of the Federation of Thai Textile
Industries, as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Thai exports are likely to gain a competitive price
advantage only against Chinese exports, as a result of a strong
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Thai exports in September totaled 171 billion baht (4.28
billion dollars), up 52 percent compared with the same month last
year. But when the depreciation of the baht is taken into account,
the actual increase is substantially lower, Viroj said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the currency crisis among ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) members will also cause Thai exports to
the region to drop, as a result of their weakening currencies.
</P>
<P>
Viroj urged the government to take measures quickly to boost
the country's productivity and competitiveness and cut production
costs so as to retain and expand Thailand's share in the world
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
