<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Likely to Get Bailout of 57 Billion USD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is expected to
receive a bailout loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, its Deputy
Premier Lim Chang-yuel said today.
</P>
<P>
Lim, also the Minister of Finance and Economy, announced that
three more nations - Belgium, the Netherland and Sweden - agreed
to contribute rescue funds totaling two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the IMF has promised 21 billion U.S. dollars; the
World Bank, 10 billion; the Asian Development Bank, four billion;
and the United States, Japan, France, Canada, Germany, the United
Kingdom, Australia, 20 billion in the aggregate.
</P>
<P>
After the IMF's executive board approved the bailout package,
the agency will send its first tranche Friday afternoon to the
Bank of Korea (BOK)'s account opened at the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board, an official from the BOK said.
</P>
<P>
The first installment of about 5 billion U.S. dollars will
arrive in Seoul early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The official said the credit rating of South Korea's financial
institutions will be recouped as the delivery of the IMF financial
aids tends to serve as a kind of payment guarantee for the
receiving country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
