<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Province of China Signs Cooperation Agreements with Denmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan, a major agricultural
province in southwest China, recently signed with Denmark 11
agreements on economic and technical cooperation in the
agricultural and animal husbandry sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, a Danish investment delegation,
headed by Christopher Bo Bramsen, Danish Ambassador to China,
toured the province and attended the '97 Sichuan-Denmark Economic
and Technological Symposium on agriculture and animal husbandry
held in the provincial capital of Chengdu recently.
</P>
<P>
The delegation visited the province at the invitation of
Sichuan Provincial Council for Promotion of International Trade,
which signed a long-term cooperation agreement with the Danish
Agricultural Association. Various local companies also signed
contracts with Danish firms calling for cooperation in the meat
processing and animal breeding sectors.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has developed the world's most advanced pork processing
technology and equipment. One Danish company has decided to
cooperate with local companies to jointly invest 20 million
U.S. dollars in a modern meat processing factory in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has more than 4.54 million ha. of arable land, or
approximately 12 percent of the national total, and produces
grain, oil-bearing crops, cocoons and pork, among others. The
province is also one of China's five pastoral areas and leads the
nation in pork production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
