<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 90,000 College Graduates to Choose Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- In China, the state used to pay
college fees for students and assign them to jobs after
graduation. But this is changing.
</P>
<P>
Under new state guidelines, 90,000 students who are expected to
graduate from college next year will make their own decisions in
choosing jobs.
</P>
<P>
These graduates, 10 percent of the class of '98, will be the
first since China adopted the "pay-to-learn" reform of the
educational system in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) chose 46 colleges and
universities to execute a pilot program in 1994. The reform was
extended to 660 schools last year, and to all colleges and
universities this year.
</P>
<P>
The reform's goal is to establish a system where students pay
some college fees and are allowed to choose their own jobs upon
graduation.
</P>
<P>
However, scholarships are being offered for graduates who fill
specific needs around the country.
</P>
<P>
An SEC official said the reform ensures that the enrollment
system will be a "fair competition" for every student.
</P>
<P>
Choosing their own jobs has become a trend for graduates in
China. By 1999, 50 percent of college graduates in Beijing will
decide what kind of job they take, according to an official from
Beijing Municipal Education Committee. By 2001, all graduate
students in the country will choose their own jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
