<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Candidates Cleared in Kenya's Presidency Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 15 candidates have
been cleared to run for the presidency in Kenya's December 29
elections, the most crowded presidential race since the country
declared independence in early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, 74 and in power
for 19 years, is widely expected to win the campaign with
five-year more tenure largely due to the division of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Moi is the sole candidate of the ruling Kenya African National
Union (KANU) party.
</P>
<P>
His powerful rivals include Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party of
Kenya, Wamalwa Kijana of FORD-Kenya, Raila Odinga of National
Development Party of Kenya, Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic
Party and Martin Shikuku of FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
Ngilu, and Wangari Maathai from Liberal Party of Kenya are the
first women ever to vie for the highest political office in the
eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Oludhe's Economic Independence Party, established 11
days ago, is the youngest party in the race, while the
37-year-old KANU the oldest.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates are Munyua Waiyaki of United Patriotic Party
of Kenya, George Anyona of Kenya Social Congress, Kimani wa
Nyoike of FORD-People, Koigi Wamwere of Kenda, David Ng'ethe of
Umma Patriotic Party of Kenya, Godfrey M'Mwireria of Green
African Party and Katama Mkangi of Kenya National Congress.
</P>
<P>
A presidential aspirant can be qualified as he/she gets the
mandatory 1,000 signatures of supporters. But to be a legal
Kenyan president, it takes no less than 25 percent votes in five
out of the country's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll, released by Kenya Institute of Education and
Democracy Thursday when the two-day presidential nominations
ended, predicted that Moi will garner 41 percent of the total
votes cast.
</P>
<P>
He will be followed by Kibaki and Ngilu with 14 and 13 percent
of votes respectively, according to the poll, which was carried
out in 42 constituencies over the weekend with more than 3,000
Kenyans interviewed.
</P>
<P>
Voting will be carried out along ethnic lines with most of the
opposition candidates only obtaining the 25 percent majority in
their home provinces, said the poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
