<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Advertising to Be Banned in EU (updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- After 10 hours of heated
debate, European Union health ministers finally agreed late on
Thursday that all tobacco advertising has to phase out within six
years in the union.
</P>
<P>
Billboard advertising has to end within three years while
advertising via the mass media within four years, diplomatic
sources quoted the ministers' agreement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Plans to agree a EU-wide ban on direct and indirect tobacco
advertising and sponsorship had been thrown into disarray earlier
in the day when Spain, a long-time supporter of the ban, said it
could not support the move.
</P>
<P>
Only eight ministers favored the ban while Britain asked for a
10-year exemption for its Formula One motor racing.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Greece, Austria and Denmark had lined up either to
oppose the ban or withhold support for it while Finland, France,
Portugal and Italy already have banned tobacco advertising.
</P>
<P>
EU health commissioner Padraig Flynn had warned that he might
withdraw the commission directive proposing the ban if a deal
could not be reached at Thursday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposal was made in 1989 and it had been
discussed on 10 occasions by the EU health ministers without
reaching a common position.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed directive, EU member states will be able to
continue existing sponsorship of world-level events for a period
to be defined.
</P>
<P>
But sponsorship money have to decrease, as will the visibility
of tobacco advertising at these events.
</P>
<P>
The EU health ministers also agreed on a grace period of two
years for organizers of common events and a grace period of three
years for those of world-level events, such as the Formula One
motor racing and art events, according to diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Flynn had indicated that he would have accepted a
seven-year gap between the directive's full implementation and the
exemption being withdrawn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Slower Growth Expected, but "Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southeast Asian financial
crisis in 1997 has created a lot of uncertainty for the economic
future of Asia, but the "Asian economic miracle" is not over, as
the region could still achieve steady, though slower, growth in
the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
As the fastest-growing region in the world, Asia has always
been the source of global economic growth during the past decades.
Its economic success has been "a miracle" in the eyes of
businessmen, investors and economists.
</P>
<P>
But, in early July, a financial crisis in Thailand spread
quickly to the Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore, all
"economic tigers" in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Within months, currencies of these countries have depreciated
between 10 and 35 percent, and stock markets dropped to their
lowest in years.
</P>
<P>
The effects of the fallout have been felt not only in Southeast
Asia, but also in other parts of Asia. South Korea is experiencing
its worst market turbulence, while Japan has also been dragged
into the trouble.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath of the crisis, people began to wonder if the
"Asian miracle" is over. Some people even predicted a possible
recession in Asia.
</P>
<P>
But most economists believe that the "Asian miracle" may be
battered, but is not over.
</P>
<P>
They admit that the depth and severity of the economic slowdown
in Southeast Asia and the effects of the currency crisis on the
rest of the region are difficult to predict at the present stage.
</P>
<P>
However, Asia still has potential for steady growth in 1997 and
1998 because its economic fundamentals remain solid, they argued.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly, Southeast Asian countries, except Singapore, have
been severely hit by the crisis. The impact of the crisis -- weak
currency exchange rates, higher interest rates, increasing
non-performing loans and foreign debts -- will start to bite the
economies of Southeast Asian countries in the last quarter of this
year and the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its latest forecast, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said
that despite the measures taken by governments to improve their
fiscal positions, the economic growth in Southeast Asia will
decelerate from 7.4 percent last year to between 4.9 percent and
5.7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The growth is expected to range between 5.2 and 6.3 percent in
1998, it said.
</P>
<P>
Some economists painted an even darker picture for Southeast
Asia, predicting that the sub-region will grow at an average
annual rate of 4 percent over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Due to price hikes as a result of the crisis, inflation rate in
Southeast Asia is estimated to rise from 6.6 percent in 1996 to 9
percent in 1997, and to 11.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, the
growing pace of other parts of Asia will also slow down. ADB
economists estimated that developing Asian economies will grow
between 6.1 percent on the lower side and 7 percent on the upper
side this year.
</P>
<P>
With the effects of the Southeast Asian crisis unfolding, the
Asian economy would grow between 5.3 percent and 6.2 percent in
1998, much lower than this year's, they said.
</P>
<P>
Also because of the crisis, Asia's inflation for 1997 has been
estimated at 7.8 percent, 4.7 percent higher than last year's.
</P>
<P>
However, the lower growth rates projected for this year and
next do not necessarily mean that the "Asian miracle" is over.
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts cited the strong economic momentum in
China, the faster pace in South Asia, and export opportunities
created by currency devaluation in Southeast Asia as major factors
for the continuation of the miracle.
</P>
<P>
They said that Asia is projected to remain the fastest growing
region in the world, led by the growth of the Chinese economy,
which should be sustained in the 9 percent to 10 percent range
this year and next.
</P>
<P>
In addition, relatively solid growth is projected to continue
in India, where a reform process underway since 1992 has already
produced notable results, maintaining annual growth at about 7
percent since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The economic situation in the rest of South Asia is also
encouraging. Despite various bottlenecks, between 1994 and 1996,
their overall gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate was 6.5
percent, which represents an acceleration of the trend in the
past.
</P>
<P>
The estimated GDP growth rate for 1997 is 6.2 percent, but with
further implementation of different reform packages and
improvements in infrastructure, economies of South Asian countries
are forecast to grow on average at 6.5 percent in 1998 and 7
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The strong growth tendency both in China and South Asia will
certainly contribute to the growing momentum in the Asian region,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there are signs of export recovery in Asia which would
also stimulate the economic growth in the region in the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a lower demand in the world electronics market and
appreciation of Southeast Asian currencies, which were pegged to
the U.S. dollar, resulted in sharp declines of Asia's exports.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, the situation has changed this year with the
recovery of the electronics market and depreciation of Southeast
Asian currencies, which has made Southeast Asian products more
competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Although uncertainty remains for Asia's economic future,
economists believe that the "Asian miracle" is not over.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science and Technology Promote Grain Production in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Science and technology
applications have directly contributed to 43 percent of the total
grain production in northeast China, seven percentage points
higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang, Liaoning, and Jilin provinces, a region known as
north China's granary, have adopted techniques such as
intercropping maize and wheat, and using special fertilizer
applications. The method has helped to increase grain yields on
many fields by as much as 15 tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
It took Heilongjiang 17 years to push its annual grain
output by five billion kilograms from the figure 40 years
ago. However, the province recorded annual grain production
increases of five billion kg on two occassions during the 1990s,
with said increases achieved within two and four year
periods. Science and technology played a key role in the
achievement, according to local government officials.
</P>
<P>
The three provinces have also increased efforts to promote the
use of practical agricultural techniques. Heilongjiang has
established two agrobiology promotion stations serving more than
1,300 townships. The stations have trained some 21,600
agricultural technicians for 15,000 villages, with 30,000
households serving as role models in the use of science and
technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Aerospace Blueprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today launched
its Blueprint for the Development of the Aerospace Industry in a
bid to make it one that will be "globally-competitive and widely
acknowledged".
</P>
<P>
Launching the blueprint in northern Malaysia's resort island
Langkawi where the Fourth Langkawi International Maritime and
Aerospace (LIMA) Exhibition is held, Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad also announced the formation of a high-level
committee led by himself and the upgrading of the Department of
the Civil Aviation (DCA) to strengthen the industry, according to
official reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian Agency for Space Administration (MASA)
would also be formed to spur Malaysia's entry into the space
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said MASA would ensure the efficient management of the
country's space venture which included the development of a
national satellite program where it could help develop the
industrial and technology capability in this area.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir stressed that the aerospace industry could not afford
to be too divergent and fragmented, saying it was imperative that
the industry should adopt the national vision as its main thrust
and approach the aerospace development task on a consolidated
basis.
</P>
<P>
"This will provide a nationally consistent framework for
identifying and evaluating key initiatives to be developed," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for a start, the blueprint, which was completed
last year and endorsed by the Cabinet last September, recommended
the establishment of a national level Steering Committee to
oversee the development of the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
This committee in the form of a national aerospace council
would make key decisions in the areas of directions, priorities
and strategies for the industry, and the council would adopt the
"Smart Partnership" principles with the participation of leaders
from both the public and private sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the council, the government also supported the
idea of a national aerospace coordinating body to act as a
reference point for the various aerospace activities and
investments and the new body will consolidate the current national
initiatives in the aerospace sector and further spearhead
Malaysia's involvement in the industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that taking into account the industry expansion
into new and unexplored territory of aerospace activities, the
existing DCA would have to be upgraded while the proposed Civil
Aviation Authority would provide the industry with a monitoring
as well as regulatory function in the areas of air worthiness, air
traffic control and aerospace products and services.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that a National Human Resource Development
Program would be put in place to ensure adequate and competitive
skills and costs of personnel, saying that it would take into
account the various categories of labor required in the aerospace
industry such as toolmakers, aircraft engineers, test pilots and
systems analysts.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia also hopes to establish a premier educational
center for aerospace which will serve the domestic as well as the
regional need for education and training.
</P>
<P>
"The aerospace industry provides a gateway to technological
acquisition and therefore it is essential that these technologies
acquired through procurement and offset would help the nation to
gain access to a foreign market and fully realize our national
competitive advantage," he said.
</P>
<P>
For the successful implementation of the key programs, Mahathir
said, the industry must be equally supported by policies which are
both rational and enhancing.
</P>
<P>
"A national procurement policy which emphasizes local products
and services and technology will ensure a sustainable economic
development and reduce import and financial outflow," he said.
</P>
<P>
This policy is important in the procurement of military
equipment, privatization projects and offset programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the focus of the recommendations in the blueprint
was on the government because it set the legislative framework and
policy. "However, the success of the industry will be a
responsibility that goes much farther than the government. Action
and participation are required of all the stakeholders," he added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
