<HEADLINE> Museum Set Up in East China City to Display Historical Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A museum has been opened to
the public here recently to display historical relics in ancient
Nanjing, now the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing, known as Jinling in ancient times, was the
capital of six dynasties or kingdoms, namely, the Wu Kingdom
(222-280), the Eastern Jin Dynasty (317-420), the Song, Qi, Liang
and Chen kingdoms of the Southern Dynasties (420-589). It was also
the center of science, technology, culture and art in Asia. So it
has a lot of historical relics.
</P>
<P>
The museum, which covers 1,000 sq.m., features 300
pieces of precious historical relics unearthed in and near the
city over the past 50 years. Pottery and porcelain items on
exhibit are highly valuable for archeological and historical
studies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign glass products and diamond rings on display prove that
international trade between the east and the west prospered during
the period.
</P>
<P>
The museum is equipped with a computer system, which provides
visitors with abundant information about historical events and
sites, noted figures, documents and relics in the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
