<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda to Cooperate in Maintaining Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda have decided
to establish a joint committee to to deal with security matters
on their common border, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
The authorities concerned also resolved to exchange
information related to security, to intensify mobilization for
security and to extradite criminals and their collaborators.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting held on December 3 in Ruhengeri district,
northern Rwanda, the Ruhengeri district authorities in Rwanda and
their counterparts in Uganda's Kiroro, Kabale districts exchanged
information concerning security on the common border.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said there are hundreds former Rwandan
government soldiers operating in the areas bordering Uganda. They
penetrated into Uganda from time to time, harassing residents,
according to local media.
</P>
<P>
But at the Wednesday meeting, Ruhengeri authorities expressed
suspicion that Uganda district authorities gave sanctuary to
Rwandan anti-government elements.
</P>
<P>
But the Ugandan officials noted that it is not the Ugandan
government's policy to give sanctuary to the Rwandan criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
