<HEADLINE> EU Bans Tobacco Ads, Sports Sponsoring by Cigarette Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, Belgium, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union
(EU) has voted on Thursday here to ban most tobacco advertising
within four years and given cigarette makers until October 2006 to
end their sponsorship of major sports and cultural events .
</P>
<P>
That means those events such as, Formular One car racing,
tennis tournaments and yacht races can have nine more seasons with
financial support from tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
Until last month, Britain had long opposed an advertising and
sponsoring ban, at last agreed to give a temporary exemption for
Formula One racing. The sport provides 50,000 jobs in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the popular Formula One races, which gets about
200 million U.S. dollars from the tobacco industry, said in
advance of the EU meeting that a tobacco ban would force them to
withdraw many if not all of the 10 European Grand Prix races from
Europe and go to Asia instead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
