<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trees Now Cover Once Barren County in Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- On the vast, barren Loess
Plateau of northwestern China, Jingchuan County stands out like a
"kingdom of forest."
</P>
<P>
Poplar, pine and Chinese scholar trees grow well along county
roads in eastern Gansu Province. The forest cover in Jingchuan
County has increased to 34.9 percent. Four decades ago, it was
just 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The county used to suffer soil erosion over 98.6 percent of its
territory. More than 2,480 ravines have been formed because of the
Jinghe River.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, local farmers have been organized to grow
trees in the spring, build terraced fields in the summer, and
control small drainage areas in autumn.
</P>
<P>
Growing grass, planting trees and constructing terraced fields
are considered necessary work to protect the land for younger
generations.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have leveled farmland, built terraced fields along the
slopes of ravines and planted trees around fields to conserve
water.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts have paid off. Land that could not retain water,
soil or fertilizer has been converted to high-yield grain fields.
</P>
<P>
So far, 82.4 percent of the region's soil erosion has been
arrested, setting off a positive ecological cycle. Rural
residents no longer starve, and many households have been able to
store surplus grain for future needs.
</P>
<P>
Artificially grown dense forests not only prevent soil erosion,
but also provide local farmers with plenty of fuel, fodder for
livestocks and material for building houses. Felling trees is
controlled to protect the region's eco-system.
</P>
<P>
County authorities have combined water conservation with
industrialized farming in recent years to help farmers rise above
the poverty line and even prosper.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the Ministry of Water Resources chose Jingchuan as one
of the counties to experiment with a combination of soil erosion
control and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers have been developing major businesses such as
growing forests and fruit trees, and turning previously low-yield
farmland and terraced fields into money-making ventures.
</P>
<P>
Guanshan Forest Farm, which used to be treeless, is now called
the "forest park" of the Loess Plateau, where wolves and leopards
have begun to roam again. More than 90 percent of the county's
farmland now is protected by trees.
</P>
<P>
A German expert on an inspection tour said naturally occurring
forests would be unlikely here, but trees now cover the Loess
Plateau because of the farmers' efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
