<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Relics Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists recently
discovered relics of an ancient ethnic group in Yuanqu County in
north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The ancient town of Yuanqu, on the northern bank of the Yellow
River, was a battlefield between the Han people and the Gaoluoshi
people, an ethnic group in the Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770-256 B.C.)
</P>
<P>
Archeologists excavated an ancient tomb near the west gate of
the Yuanqu county seat, and discovered that the earthenware
unearthed in the tomb differed greatly from the items of the same
period found in the tombs of the Han people.
</P>
<P>
The different designs, colors and decorations on the relics
showed that the person interred in the tomb was not a member of
the local Han community, according to archeologists.
</P>
<P>
They said the county was most likely inhabited by members of the
Gaoluoshi ethnic group which historical books refer to as the "Chidi".
</P>
<P>
Archeologists studying the relics believe the items will
provide valuable clues to relations between the ethnic groups and the
Han in the Eastern Zhou Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Engulfs Ship in Southern Philippine Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Fire destroyed a major ferry
undergoing portside refurbishing at Mandaue city, Southern
Philippines, last night, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
About 100 workers were doing repair and restoration work on the
4,717-ton steel-hulled Philippine Princess of Sulpicio Lines
company when sparks from a welding rod apparently ignited some
combustible materials on board, it said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted witnesses as saying that the workers
scampered away for safety, leaving no one to help put out the
fire, which soon spread throughout the ship.
</P>
<P>
A tugboat belonging to Carlos Gothong Shipping Lines and two
Coast Guard patrol craft battled the fire with small hoses being
fed with sea water from small pumps, it said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the three boats first towed the stricken vessel
toward the middle of Cebu harbor to spare other ships docked at
portside, rendering useless the arrival of fire trucks from Cebu
city and Mandaue city.
</P>
<P>
Cebu Coast Guard Commander Franklin Llanto said his men would
help in the investigation of the incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
