<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Leads in Child Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- As many as 23.6 million child
laborers aged between 10 and 14, or about one-third of the
world's 73 million child workers, are in Africa, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Africa leads in relative terms with the highest number of
child workers," Elias Mabere, the Assistant Director-General of
the International Labor Organization who is responsible for
Africa, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The trend in Africa is due to high population growth rates,
degrading conditions of living brought about by economic
hardships and the incapacity of the existing educational systems
to cater for all school-aged children, he added.
</P>
<P>
In sub-Saharan Africa, the problem was caused by increasing
rural poverty and the accelerated rural-urban migration in search
of job opportunities, he said at the on-going International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions Africa Region conference here.
</P>
<P>
The most pervasive and degrading forms of abuse involved
forced and bonded labor, commercial sexual exploitation and the
use of children in drug-trafficking, he said at the three-day
meeting which is to end tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called for all countries involved to adopt and
supervise international labor standards so as to combat child
labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Kidnap Suspects Killed in Manila Shoot-out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Two kidnap suspects were killed
while a policeman was wounded in a shoot-out in the Philippine
capital of Manila this morning.
</P>
<P>
One of the suspects was killed instantly while the other died
on arrival at a hospital as he sustained multiple gunshot wounds,
police said.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out, which took place along E. Rodriguez Blvd.,
Cubao, Quezon city, around 11:00 p.m. today, involved a group of
policemen from the Central Police District Command who had been
following for about two weeks the movements of suspected members
of a kidnap gang.
</P>
<P>
Police said the gang was to meet with their cohorts in Cubao
when the shoot-out took place. The suspects apparently sensed that
they were being followed by lawmen, police said.
</P>
<P>
The suspects jumped out of the cab and opened fire at the
pursuing lawmen. One of the three suspects managed to escape, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, 98 kidnap incidents were
reported to the police in the first nine months this year compared
with 47 last year. More than 200 people were kidnapped in the
incidents this year and most of the victims were Filipino-Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The latest spate of kidnapping in the country has aroused
strong protests among the Chinese community in the Philippines. On
Tuesday, shops in Manila's Chinatown and Chinese schools in the
capital were closed in protest of the government's inability to
stop such crime.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to President Fidel Ramos on Thursday, the
Chinese community urged the government to take "more sincere,
concerted, decisive and effective actions" to stop kidnappings.
</P>
</TEXT>
