<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science, Technology Revitalize National Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The improvement of China's
fiscal situation is a direct result of the nation's emphasis on
science and technology, said a top legislator in a signed article
carried in today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Wang Bingqian, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), said that only the sustained
development of science and technology will help the nation tap
major revenue resources.
</P>
<P>
The NPC vice-chairman commented on the great changes wrought by
science and technology in agriculture, industry, and the service
sector. For instance, per-unit area outputs of rice, wheat, and
corn in China surpass those of the world average by 26-to-51
percent. The overall yield per hectare is 8.5 times as much as two
decades ago when China began its reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
China began to renovate its traditional industries and develop
new ones with advanced technologies from abroad in the 1980s. It
has generated impetus for economic development and created
conditions for sustainable revenue growth, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
China's high-tech enterprises have generated 15 percent of the
country's gross industrial output, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"Science and technology promote rapid development of the
productive forces on one hand and produce enormous economic and
social returns on the other hand," he said.
</P>
<P>
"With development and popularization of various high-tech
businesses, taxation paid by newly developed industries and their
products have become an important financial resource that helps
increase the country's revenue," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The development of science, technology and education requires
national support, he said. Without financial aid from the state,
it would be very difficult for researchers to make necessary
breakthroughs. With financial support from the government,
knowledge gained through scientific research can be transferred
from laboratories to business workshops.
</P>
<P>
The NPC vice-chairman concluded that science and technology
supplements national revenue. While intensifying economic growth,
China should consider the role science and technology play in
developing the national economy, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Credits for India's Education Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved two credits totaling 211.4 million U.S. dollars for two
educational projects in India.
</P>
<P>
A credit of some 59.4 million dollars will be used for the
second Utta Pradesh basic education project, which includes the
building of new schools and additional classrooms, the recruiting
and training of new teachers, the establishmnent of school
improvement funds and the provision of learning materials.
</P>
<P>
The project will benefit 600,000 children aged six to ten and
200,000 in the 11-13 age group, bringing the enrollment rates of
the targeted districts from 88 percent to 100 percent in primary
education and from 43 percent to 75 percent in higher primary
education by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The other credit of 152 million dollars is earmarked for
India's third district primary education project to cut school
dropout rate and expand school access.
</P>
<P>
The credit will help the state of Bihar to enroll more than 5.5
million school-age children in 17 disadvantaged districts and
double its enrollment rates by the end of the five-year project.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's lending arm for
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
