<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Sustained Development in Township Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- China's rural industry met all
economic targets in the first 10 months of this year, a
government official on township-run industry said here today.
</P>
<P>
The rural industrial enterprises gained an added value of 745.8
billion yuan in the first 10 months of this year, up 15.6 percent
from the same period last year, said Jiang Yongtao, director of
the Township-run Industry Bureau under the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Business turnover totalled 3.28 trillion yuan in the first 10
months, up 17.6 percent; and profit rose to 130 billion yuan, up
18 percent. The ratio between output and market sales was 92.5
percent, he told a national conference on rural industrial
development held today in Hefei, capital of east China's Anhui
Province.
</P>
<P>
Nine billion U.S. dollars in investment have been attracted
from abroad for construction and expansion of rural
enterprises. More than 3,600 rural firms have started their
operations overseas.
</P>
<P>
Many enterprises have experimented with a diversified form of
ownership such as the stock partnership system, stock
cooperatives, leasing, mergers and formation of enterprise groups
in an effort to reorganize collective assets.
</P>
<P>
So far, rural China established 3.5 million stock cooperatives,
of which, 240,000, or 15 percent of the total, are collectively
owned firms, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said development of township-run enterprises in eastern
China grew by 15.8 percent; central China, 14.7 percent; and
western China, 18.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Jiang stated, problems still exist in the economic
operation of rural industries. About 15 percent of township-run
enterprises suffered losses, seven percent higher than last year's
figure.
</P>
<P>
Jiang attributed the increased losses to rising production
costs and lower profits, non-production expenditures, a sluggish
market and insufficient operation funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Beefs up Efforts to Stop Spread of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has worked
out a new comprehensive program to prevent the proliferation of
firearms in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Law and Order said on Thursday that the plan
was aimed at reducing the number of firearms, both legal and
illgal in private hands.
</P>
<P>
Controlling firearms will be done by way of stopping the flow
of illegal firearms into South Africa, preventing the theft of
legal firearms and taking active steps to reduce the existing
pool of firearms.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Safety and Security Joe Matthews said the
proliferation of firearms in South Africa has been a matter of
great concern to the government.
</P>
<P>
According to an official statistics, some 41 percent of all
murders and 76 percent of all robberies in 1996 were committed
with firearms. During the period from January 1996 to November
this year, a total of 50,585 legally registered firearms were
stolen or lost.
</P>
<P>
Estimates put the total number of illegal fireams in South
Africa at as much as four million with a further 3.76 milion
legally licensed firearms.
</P>
<P>
To stop the inflow of arms into South Africa, additional
firearms investigation units will be established to trace illegal
firearms in cooperation with other departments and even other
countries.
</P>
<P>
A Central Import-Control Office has been set up to control the
legal importing of firearms.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the theft of legal firearms, designated firearms
controlling officers will be appointed at police station level.
</P>
<P>
These officers will ensure that all applicants for firearms
are qualified and that such applicants have the necessary safes
to store the firearms and that applicants have completed a
competency test.
</P>
<P>
Other steps include linking state databases to ensure that
stolen firearms are not later legally licensed and dealers would
be physicaly checked to see if they had stolen firearms in stock.
</P>
<P>
Penalties for illegal firearms will be increased from five
years to 10 years in prison, and a person who loses a firearms
will be sentenced up to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
All the measures would be in place within the next two years,
Law and Order Ministry officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
