<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Growth for Shanghai Consumer Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The consumer market in
Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, is expected to maintain
moderately rapid growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A local commercial official predicted that the city's retail
sales of consumer goods for the year will rise by 10-12 percent,
and will end at a level between 145.8-148.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed growth in the city's consumer market to
national macroeconomic development and Shanghai's position as an
international financial, economic and trade center.
</P>
<P>
Other favorable factors include a plentiful supply of goods,
bumper grain harvest, planned increases for investments in fixed
assets, growing demand for exports and implementation of the
shareholder system.
</P>
<P>
However, local analysts noted a decline in the purchasing power
of local residents due to an increase in the number of people
laid-off, slow growth in wages, expanded investment channels and
rising noncommercial expenses for items such as education, tourism
and telecommunications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
