<HEADLINE> Australia to Contribute to South Pacific Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Australia said today it would
contribute nearly 8 million Australian dollars (about 5.5 million
U.S. dollars) to the South Pacific Commission (SPC), a premier
regional development agency in the region, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The grant includes an agreed share of core operating costs
(about 2 million U.S dollars) and additional funding for specific
projects and programs, including a new initiative to support
training of Pacific islanders in a coastal fisheries program and
increased support for a women's program, Kathy Sullivan,
parliamentary secretary to Australian Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer said in a statement today.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, AusAID, an Australian official overseas
body, will fund a number of SPC regional health programs including
one on HIV/AIDS prevention and mosquito-borne disease control,
</P>
<P>
Australia remains the largest single donor of the SPC, to be
known as the Pacific Community from February 1998, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
