<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Passes New Income Tax Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of
Bulgaria, the top legislature of the country, today passed a new
tax law to extend the coverage on personal incomes.
</P>
<P>
The new law will be effective from January 1, 1998, to replace
the current Aggregate Income Taxation Act.
</P>
<P>
The law "completes the first stage of the tax reform we
promised to carry out," Yordan Tsonev, chairman of the Budget and
Finance Parliamentary Committee, told journalists.
</P>
<P>
Despite the restrictive provisions contained in the
legislation, Tsonev said, it will ensure the economic growth
projected for 1998 and promote business development in general.
</P>
<P>
If the reform goes on smoothly and tax collectability is
improved, the tax burden will diminish progressively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, incomes derived from wage, trade, crafts
practicing, free-lancing, real estate sales and swaps, the sale of
shares and stakes, rent, leasing premiums or rents are all taxable.
</P>
<P>
It sets three deadlines for paying license tax: January 31,
July 31 and October 31. Those who pay the amount in full before
the first deadline are entitled to a five percent tax break.
</P>
<P>
Following a heated debate, the parliament approved lifting the
tax threshold for monthly and annual wage incomes from 50,000 leva
(about 31.7 U.S. dollars) now to 60,000 leva (38 dollars) in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
