<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhongyuan Records Breakthrough in Oil Prospecting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Industrial oil recently
gushed from the No.8 Well in the Zhongyuan (Central China) Oil
Field in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The event marked a breakthrough in oil prospecting in the field
and ushered in a new era for prospecting on 2,000 sq.km. of
surrounding land.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongyuan Oil Field entered production in 1979, with
exploration efforts focusing on Puyang in central China's Henan
Province and Dongming in east China's Shandong Province. Fourteen
wells are currently producing oil.
</P>
<P>
The oil field has witnessed a dramatic drop in crude oil output
since 1988 when it produced a record 7.22 million tons, with the
current annual output standing at only four million tons due to a
shortage of proven reserves.
</P>
<P>
According to the Zhongyuan Petroleum Prospecting
Administration, the No.8 Well will reach a depth of 6,000 meters,
by the end of 1997. The well is designed to study the distribution
of oil reserves in a subsiding region east of Puyang.
</P>
<P>
The No.4 Well Drilling Company has drilled to a depth of
4,647.93 meters since May 9, 1997. An oil-bearing strata was
verified at 4,102 meters and the source bed was discovered at a
depth of 4,383 meters.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the findings indicate that the Zhongyuan Oil Field
has the potential for new reserves and increased output.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
