<HEADLINE> Young HKSAR Team for Women's AHF Cup in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A young-blood team from the
Hong Kong Hockey Association left here on Friday for Singapore,
to compete in the First Women's Asian Hockey Federation (AHF)
Cup set for December 6 to 14.
</P>
<P>
The tournament, like the one held here last week with the host
coming out as the winner, is a second-tier field hockey event
for AHF-affiliated members other than China, Japan, South Korea
and India which form the first tier.
</P>
<P>
The tournament is meant to provide a chance for a high-level
and good-quality international competition for the teams.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, Hong Kong is to play in a round-robin
competition against Sri Lanka, Singapore, Chinese Taipei and
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
In the Hong Kong squad, there are five school girls who
finished second in the under-16 tournament in Singapore last
December.
</P>
<P>
"We've selected a very young team and inexperienced side for
the tournament. Our focus is on the future and this event will be
a huge learning experience for many players," said Adi Glancy,
coach of the team.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the trip is to lay the foundation for a strong
Hong Kong team for future competitions.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the 16 players are "home grown" ones, having
learned and developed their field hockey skills in Hong
Kong. "This owes to the many years of hard work by dedicated
members of the hockey community who unconditionally support the
sport in Hong Kong," said Brenda Smith, chairman of the Hong
Kong Hockey Association Women's Section.
</P>
<P>
"The number of young players joining our league is very
encouraging. Together with the large number of players from our
universities and other tertiary institutes, the league is
continuously getting new blood.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the trend will go on so that we can bring more home
grown players to the squad," the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
