<HEADLINE> Japan to Take Action to Stop Yen's Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka said today that the monetary authorities are ready to
take action to stop yen's devaluation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Excessive movements in currency exchange markets are
undesirable," Mitsuzuka told a regular press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Stability in currency markets is important for the global
economy," he stressed, adding that he will keep a close watch over
the movements.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was quoted at 129.66-68 yen at noon in Tokyo,
and dealers said it might break through the 130-yen line soon.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the Japanese economy is now in a tough
situation, Mitsuzuka said the government will analyze it carefully
before announcing any assessment.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, head of Japan's Economic Planning Agency Koji Omi
acknowledged that the country's economy is at a standstill, not in
the process of recovery. Japan's economic growth rate for fiscal
1997 will be less than one percent, far below the government's
target of 1.9 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will take appropriate measures to stimulate
the economy, Mitsuzuka added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
