<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Prime Minister-Designate Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime
Minister-Designate Jenny Shipley reshuffled the cabinet today
before being sworn in next Monday.
</P>
<P>
She dumped Defense Minister Paul East from the cabinet, who has
made it clear that he is unlikely to stay in the parliament much
longer and is considering a diplomatic posting, TVNZ reported.
</P>
<P>
The defense portfolio has now gone to Minister of Labor,
Energy, Immigration and Business Development Max Bradford.
</P>
<P>
Ex-Prime Minister Jim Bolger has been named minister of state
and associate minister of foreign affairs, both posts being
outside the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Shipley has brought two new faces into the cabinet,
Conservation Minister Nick Smith and backbench MP Tony Ryall.
</P>
<P>
Five existing cabinet members have also been promoted. They are
Education Minister Wyatt Creech, Minister of Research, Science and
Technology Maurice Williamson, Social Welfare Minister Roger
Sowry, Commerce Minister John Luxton and Health Minister Bill
English.
</P>
<P>
The report said all those having played a major role in the
coup in early November which deposed Bolger have been rewarded.
</P>
<P>
But two other members, Environment Minister Simon Upton and
Housing Minister Murray McCully have been demoted alongside
Foreign Minister Don McKinnon, who was replaced by Creech as
deputy leader of the National Party Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Forces Reduction Goodwill Gesture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The decision to reduce ground
and naval forces in northwest Russia, announced by President Boris
Yeltsin in Sweden, is part of Russia's military reform, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made a goodwill gesture toward the Baltic states
Wednesday, telling the Swedish parliament that Russia would reduce
its ground and naval forces in northwest Russia by 40 percent by
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The President also suggested that a "hot line" be set up
between militaries of Kaliningrad in Russia and three Baltic
states to supervise the territorial space of the Baltics and to
strengthen mutual trust in the region.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Gennady Tarasov, spokesman of Russian
Foreign Ministry, said the suggestion would further the
implementation of the Treaty on Conventional Armed Forces in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov asked the Western countries to clearly define their
army building plans in accordance with current security situation
in Europe. He expressed Russia's willingness to consider any
suggestion put forward by them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Stocks Finish Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wellington, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
closed slightly higher today as the Reserve Bank's statement that
the monetary conditions have eased too far had little effect on
equities despite a jump in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The NZSE40 Index ended two points higher at 2394 with a light
turnover of 40 million dollars (24 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Among the main leaders, Air New Zealand rose 1 cent to 240
cents, Carter Holt Harvey 5 cents to 255 cents, Lion Nathan 1 cent
to 388 cents and Telecom 7 cents to an all-time high of 890 cents.
</P>
<P>
On the weaker side, Brierley Investment lost 1 cent to 122
cents and Fletcher Building 20 cents to 445 cents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
