<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Bank Reform in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved a loan equivalent to 20 million U.S. dollars to help
reform Indonesia's banking system.
</P>
<P>
The loan is the first part of the bank's pledge of 4.5 billion
U.S. dollars for an international financial package in the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
The package, announced on October 31, 1997, is aimed at
supporting Indonesia's structural adjustment reforms and
stabilization program.
</P>
<P>
As well as the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and
the Asian Development Bank will also fund the package with a
respective 10 and 3.5 billion U.S. dollars. Financing promises
from other countries and regions total 15 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
