<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Urges Donors to Help Develop Hill Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh needs financial
support from donor countries and agencies to carry out development
programs for the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) that have just
signed a peace accord with the government, local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
Briefing heads of missions and representatives of donor
countries and agencies here Thursday on the CHT peace agreement
signed Tuesday, Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria said financial
assistance would be needed for the implementation of both
short-term and long-term programs for the CHT.
</P>
<P>
Additional resources would be required for resettling refugees,
developing infrastructure and other medium- and long-term
development projects in the hill districts, the finance minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that all tribal people would soon return
home, resume a normal life and contribute to the development and
prosperity of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The government has given special attention to the hill tracts
and some special facilities would be created for the area, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Immediate construction of infrastructure facilities like
schools, clinics, rural feeder roads and village markets are
urgently needed, the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
Development endeavors have been hindered over the years in the
hill districts, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for maintaining the momentum of the peace
process to help the hill districts return to normal conditions.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of development partners of Bangladesh hailed
the signing of the peace agreement and at the same time sought
detailed information on refugee resettlement and development
programs in the hill tracts, the press reports quoted Bangladeshi
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Their response to the government initiatives for development
in the region is very positive," the officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan-China Relationas Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Relations between Kazakhstan
and China have been developing smoothly, Kazakh Foreign Minister
Kasymzhomart Tokayev and visiting Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister
Zhang Deguang said here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who arrived here today for his two-day visit, held talks
with Tokayev. Both hoped that Kazakh-Chinese ties would maintain
the current momentum of development.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said Kazakhstan and China continued high-level
exchanges every year. The successful visit paid by Chinese Premier
Li Peng and Vice Deputy Premier Li Langqing last September helped
this development.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said China has persistently supported efforts Kazakhstan
made. He expressed appreciation for the proposal to hold a
conference on establishing trust among the Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakhstan signed a series of agreements, including
one for broadening cooperation in gas and oil fields, during the
visit paid by Premier Li Peng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
