<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from the Latin American countries over the
last few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Supermarket sales increased 12.4 percent in October
compared to the same month of 1996, said the Chilean Supermarkets
Guild Association.
</P>
<P>
Sales increase 6.1 percent during the first 10 months of the
year over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's manufacturing sector increased
production by 8.2 percent during the first three quarters of this
year, compared with the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to the growth in domestic sales and to
exports, said Uruguayan acting Industry, Energy and Mines Minister
Pedro Antmann.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua's exports in 1997 will total 812 million
dollars, a 21 percent growth over the 670 million dollars of last
year, according to sources with Central Bank of Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The price of gasoline will increase 16
percent next January in Colombia, said the Mines and Industry
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Ministry spokesmen said the hike of price will match that of
inflation in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The El Nino warm ocean current has caused heavy
losses in the agricultural production of the Central American
countries and some of the Caribbean nations, said the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina rolled out 44,600 motor vehicles in
November, or 18.3 percent less compared to the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association said 23,477
vehicles were exported, mainly to Brazil, in the same month, 18
percent down from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's soybeans exports reached 8.2 million
metric tons this year, up 121 percent over 1996, said the
Brazilian Association of Vegetable Oils Industries.
</P>
<P>
The country's soybean exports next year is likely to total 7.5
million tons, or 8.5 percent less compared to this year, according
to the association's projection. 
</P>
