<HEADLINE> French, German FMs: NATO Presence in Bosnia Essential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- French and German foreign
ministers today called for peacekeepers to stay in Bosnia after
their current mandate expires by the end of June next year.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and his German
counterpart Klaus Kinkel said it's essential to maintain the
presence of the NATO-led multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
The reason, they explained at a joint news conference in
Sarajevo, is that only a small part of the so-called Dayton accord
to bring peace back to Bosnia has been implemented up to now.
</P>
<P>
Other parts of the agreement, especially those on civil
procedures, are yet to be settled, they told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers were in Sarajevo to meet Bosnian
leaders and prepare a meeting scheduled for December 9-10 in Bonn
of the committee that oversees the Dayton accord's implementation.
</P>
<P>
During their one-day stay, they met Biljana Plavsic, president
of the Bosnian Serb republic, and other top Serb and Croatian
leaders. 
