<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves $21 Bln Stand-By Credit for South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved South Korea's request for a three-year
stand-by credit equivalent to about 21 billion U.S. dollars in
support of the government's economic and financial program.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, about 5.56 billion dollars is available
immediately while about 3.58 billion dollars will be available on
December 18 following the first review under the program.
</P>
<P>
Another 2 billion dollars will be available on January 8, 1998
following the second review.
</P>
<P>
However, subsequent disbursement will be made available subject
to the attainment of performance targets and, in some cases,
program reviews.
</P>
<P>
The IMF stand-by credit is equivalent to 1,939 percent of South
Korea's quota of about 1.09 billion dollars equivalent in the
international financial institution.
</P>
<P>
In approving South Korea's request for the stand-by credit, the
IMF made the use of the accelerated procedures established under
the emergency financing mechanism (EFM), which was adopted in
September 1995, following the bailout package for the Mexico
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The macroeconomic objectives of the program include: building
the conditions for an early return of confidence so as to limit
the unavoidable slowdown of GDP growth in 1998, containing
inflation at or below 5 percent and building international
reserves to more than two months of imports by the end of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
