accords on bilateral cooperation here today during Macedonian
Foreign Minister Blagoj Handziski's one-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
The accords covered a broad range of issues such as reducing
transit duties, setting signposts on borders and enabling
residents in the border region to have easier access to
communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
Other agreements included encouraging and protecting investment
activities, avoiding dual taxation and conducting trade and
transportation cooperations.
</P>
<P>
At a formal meeting, Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo held
an in-depth discussion with Handziski on bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Both foreign ministers told a following press conference, the
visit and the signing of the accords marked the beginning of a new
age in the development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two sides still had some disputes over the issue of
Albanian nationality in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Milo urged the Macedonian authorities to allow the teaching of
the Albanian language in the Tetove University. Handziski,
however, said the so-called Tetove University was illegal under
the Macedonian Constitution.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Tirana, the visiting Macedonian foreign
minister also met Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani, Prime
Minister Fatos Nano and President of the People's Assembly Skender
Gjinush. 
