<HEADLINE> Eighth Europe-Caribbean Conference Opens in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth Europe-Caribbean
Conference opened here today to discuss changes the European Union
proposes to the Lome Convention after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants were Barbados Prime Minister Owen
Arthur, Caribbean States Association Secretary-General Simon
Molina Duarte, and the Caribbean Community (Caricom)
Secretary-General, Edwin Carrington.
</P>
<P>
The two-day forum was organized by the Caribbean Council for
Europe with the support of Caricom and the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The current Lome Convention, the fourth of its kind, went into
force in 1991 and will expire in 1999. The agreement stipulates
that products made in the signatory countries, having risen over
45 percent in value in their home countries, are exempted tariffs
when entering the European market.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean Council for Europe was established to boost
commercial and political ties between the Caribbean and European
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
