<HEADLINE> 15 People Abducted in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen people aboard a mini-bus
were abducted at gunpoint by seven heavily-armed men in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines, Thursday, the National Police said
today.
</P>
<P>
Five of the 15 captives, including two students, were released
after several hours of captivity, by the unidentified suspects,
police said.
</P>
<P>
A joint rescue operation has been launched by the local police
and military units in Lanao del Sur Province to pursue the
suspects who are still holding 10 people.
</P>
<P>
The massive abduction was the latest in a series of kidnappings
reported this week, which have already aroused a public outcry
over the government's failure to neutralize kidnapping gangs.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, thousands of Chinese Filipinos took part in a
protest march in Downtown Manila and a funeral for a young Chinese
businessman killed by his abductors.
</P>
<P>
Chinese businesses and schools were closed down for one day
Tuesday in Chinatown and other parts of the capital city to
protest the government's incompetence to solve the kidnapping
issue plaguing the country for years.
</P>
<P>
But as the Chinese community mourned and protested Tuesday,
five more Chinese residents were held by kidnappers. One of the
captives, a son-in-law of a Chinese tycoon, was killed along with
four of his kidnappers in a shootout between the suspects and
policemen.
</P>
<P>
The Ramos government is now facing mounting pressure from the
public to improve the peace and order situation in the country as
Ramos nears the end of his term.  
</P>
