<HEADLINE> Citibank Undecided on Thai Bank Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.-based Citibank has not
yet made a decision on a reported takeover of Thailand's ailing
First Bangkok City Bank.
</P>
<P>
A definite decision is expected in three months after Citibank
completes examining the books of the Thai bank, the Bangkok Post
today quoted William Rhodes, vice president of Citibank, as saying
on Thursday after a meeting with Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
It was widely reported late last month that Citibank had agreed
to take a majority stake in the bank.
</P>
<P>
If the takeover came true, it would be the first such case
under a new rule of the Thai government that foreign investors can
hold a majority stake in Thai banks for up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have been cautious in welcoming the new
regulation for fear of loss after the 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are two bids by foreign investors to take over
Finance One plc, the largest of the 58 suspended finance
companies, whose fate will be announced by Thai Finance Minister
Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reports say only a very small number of them will be allowed to
reopen.
</P>
<P>
The German-based Westdeutsche Landesbank (WestLB) announced
Thursday that it had received approval from senior creditors
grouping more than 50 international banks to acquire Finance One
plc.
</P>
<P>
There is also a rival bid, by Credit Suisse First Boston, to
buy 70.5 percent of Finance One's equity for about 148 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both plans will be presented to a Thai government agency for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
There is the possibility that neither will be accepted, as
Finance One could also face takeover and liquidation by the
Financial Restructuring Authority, a Thai government agency whose
main responsibility is to handle the 58 finance companies
suspended earlier this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
