<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Confident of FTAA Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Trade
Minister Jose Manuel Salazar today expressed optimism that
negotiations for the creation of the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA) will start next April.
</P>
<P>
Doubts about the negotiations emerged when the United States
Congress denied President Bill Clinton the authorization to
negotiate the FTAA establishment through "the fast track."
</P>
<P>
The fast track is the commitment of the U.S. Congress with the
President of accepting or rejecting, without change, the
agreements the president negotiates with other nations.
</P>
<P>
Salazar, who presides over the preliminary FTAA negotiations,
said the U.S. president is interested in starting the negotiations
next April even if he does not have the support of his congress.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the 34 countries taking part in the FTAA
negotiations will meet in March to finalize a proposal that will
be presented for approval in the hemisphere summit to be held in
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said it is probable that President Clinton will get the
Congress authorization after the negotiations start although he
will arrive at the summit without the authorization to negotiate
through "the fast track."
</P>
<P>
The important thing was that the U.S. president had the
authorization before 2005, the date foreseen for the FTAA
establishment, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
