<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Parties Have Reservations on Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Many Sri Lankan Tamil political
parties have reservations about contesting the local government
elections to be held in the north, local press reports said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Only the Democratic People's Liberation Front, a political wing
of the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam, has
announced its intention to contest seats on the 17 local bodies in
the north.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil United Liberation Front said the ground situation is
not suitable for holding the elections at present as rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) are still active in some
areas where the elections would be held.
</P>
<P>
The Eelam People's Democratic Party stressed that many of the
day-to- day problems of the people in the north need to be solved
before politicians could take part in the local elections.
</P>
<P>
The Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front noted that
with heavy military presence in the north, elections would have no
meaning. The party also accused the military of "unnecessarily
interfering in civil affairs."
</P>
<P>
The Tamil Eelam Liberation Organization, the Eelavar Democratic
Front and other Tamil parties also expressed their concerns over
the coming elections in the north.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the parties left the door open when they said
their policy makers would meet next week to determine whether or
not they would contest the elections.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Elections Dayananda Dissanayake said on
Wednesday that nominations for general elections to municipal,
urban and village councils in Jaffna and Kilinochchi districts in
the north will be received from December 16 to 23.
</P>
<P>
The elections have been postponed for almost one year due to
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE is engaging government troops in the north and east in
a desperate effort to create an independent state of their own.
</P>
<P>
The 14-year-long war has severely interrupted the normalcy of
the regions and caused heavy casualties. At least 55,000 people
have been killed and thousands of others rendered homeless since
the war broke out in 1983.  
</P>
</TEXT>
