<HEADLINE> Canadians Lose Money at Cash Register </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are paying huge amount
of extra money to stores that aren't properly programming their
price scanners, said a study released today.
</P>
<P>
The study team visited five department stores, bought 375
items from three different stores in each of the chains, and found
errors in their bills an average of 14 percent of all times.
</P>
<P>
In nine percent of the cases, the error favored the store,
while the consumer came out ahead five percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
By average, there was a net overcharging of 2.5 percent to the
consumer as a result of scanner errors.
</P>
<P>
A similar government study a year ago found a national error
rate of 6.5 percent, and both consumers and stores came out ahead
half of the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
