<HEADLINE> Thai King Calls for More Focus on Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai King Bhumibol Adulyadej
Thursday said Thailand should focus on a self-sustained
agriculture-based economy and use more Thai goods to get rid of
the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The king made the remarks in his annual address to the nation
on television Thursday night on the eve of Thailand's national day
today, which is also the king's 70th birthday.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said the king warned against relying too much
on industry to spur a recovery and striving too hard to become one
of Asia's "tiger" economies.
</P>
<P>
"Whether to be a tiger is unimportant," the king said, "and the
important thing is for the economy to be able to support Thais."
</P>
<P>
Thailand could not rely on the same policy of producing too
much industrial goods as other countries are also in trouble and
they also do not have money to buy Thai goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although an agrarian economy might be considered outdated,
Thailand needs to take a step back at this time in order that it
can go forward in the future, the king said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has a lot of land and the government should reinforce
its technical and financial support to increase agricultural
production, the king said.
</P>
<P>
During his one-and-a-half hour speech, the king also called on
the 60 million Thai people to remain united, be frugal, abstain
from the habit of overspending and buy more Thai goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
