<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Businessmen Insist on Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican private sector
organizations proposed again today that public assets be sold as a
solution to the internal debt problem.
</P>
<P>
The debt amounts to 1.1 trillion colons (about 2.7 billion
U.S. dollars), the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for privatizing some companies, such as the state
monopolies of insurance and telecommunications, have caused
controversy in political circles.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion shows that two-thirds of Costa Ricans are
against the sale of the assets to solve the debt problem.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for the Defense of Institutionality, headed by
former President Rodrigo Carazo, said the sale would not solve the
problem, and the intention was simply for the state to get rid of
its enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Samuel Yankelewitz, president of the Costa Rican
Union of Chambers and Associations of Private Enterprise, said
today that as long as the assets were not sold, the internal debt
problem would persist.
</P>
<P>
It is not feasible that the state will promote the
privatization as a solution to the debt amid the electoral
campaign which will end in February.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Social Christian Party presidential candidate,
Miguel Angel Rodriguez, a favorite for the elections triumph,
supports the privatization and the dismantling of the state
monopolies in some economic sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
