<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Realization Still Low in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Realization level of domestic
and foreign investment in Indonesia has been low, an Indonesian
official said.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1996 survey, the realization level stood at
47.96 percent for domestic and 53.44 percent for foreign
investment, an official of the Investment Coordinating Board, R.
Iskandar, said here Thursday at a counseling meeting on the
investment policy.
</P>
<P>
Domestic investment projects since 1968 have reached 10,916
with a planned investment of 593.3 trillion rupiah (about 169.5
billion U.S. dollars), sources at the meeting today quoted
Iskandar as saying.
</P>
<P>
The foreign projects agreed since 1967 have reached 5,484 with
planned investments totaling 203.6 billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, even though the national economy is being rocked by
monetary turmoil, he said, domestic and foreign investors'
interest in Indonesia remains strong.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the value of domestic investments stood at 100.7
trillion rupiah, but this year until November 15, domestic
investments had totaled 110.8 trillion rupiah, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investments were valued at 29.92 billion
dollars in 1996, but this year they had reached 29.94 billion
dollars by November.
</P>
<P>
However, economic observers here said the realization of
domestic and foreign investment in 1997 will be lower than that in
1996 because of the current monetary crisis, which has resulted in
a drop of some 50 percent in the value of the country's currency,
the rupiah, and impaired investors' confidence in the country's
monetary sector and its economy as a whole.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
