<HEADLINE> Drought-Related Diseases Kill 656 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Starvation and drought-related
diseases have killed at least 656 people in Indonesia's remote
corner of Irian Jaya Province, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The drought, believed to be the region's worst in half a
century, and a series of forest fires since July this year have
caused failures in the harvests of rice and other crops in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a total of 447 people have died in Jayawijaya
District, 3,400 kilometers east of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross reported earlier
that at least 103 villagers had died of starvation and
drought-related diseases in Mimika District west of Jayawijaya.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the newspaper Kompas reported Thursday that 82
people have died in Merauke and 24 in Puncak Jaya districts in
Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
The central government has sent food, medicines and other
relief supplies to Irian Jaya, official sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
