<HEADLINE> Greenhouse Gas Emissions Rise in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth and the
population increase have caused the rise of greenhouse gas
emissions in Canada, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
Total greenhouse gas emissions related to Canada's household
consumption increased 14 percent between 1981 and 1992, the
Federal Statistics Agency said in its report on the country's
environmental wealth.
</P>
<P>
The increase would have been much higher if it were not for a
shift towards using natural gas and better energy efficiency, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
As to environmental wealth, the agency said that energy,
minerals and timber contributed 316 billion Canadian dollars (221
billion U.S. dollars) to the national wealth in 1995, about a
tenth of its total.
</P>
<P>
If agricultural and developed land were included, the increase
would be up to 31 percent of the national wealth, the agency
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
