<HEADLINE> Cuba Calls on Caribbean Economies To Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Vice President Carlos Lage
today urged the small Caribbean economies to unite because it was
the only solution for the area in view of the integration of big
economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
Lage told the Carribean-Europe Conference that it is impossible
for the small Caribbean economies to compete with those of the
developed countries because of the technological gap,
protectionism and other reasons.
</P>
<P>
He said Cuba's disposition to cooperate within the union of
Caribbean countries, with which Havana had a trade exchange of 400
million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"We build our relations with the Caribbean countries on the
basis of cooperation and not on competition," said Lage. He said
the Cuban government is willing to boost that linkage, for example
through technicians and qualified specialists.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Cuban relations with Europe, Lage said 29 percent
of Cuban trade is now with the European Union, compared with seven
percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A proposal by the European Union to change the finishing time
of the Fourth Lome Convention was examined during the meeting of
European and Caribbean delegates. The agreement was initially
planned to end by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the Lome Covention, the former European colonial centers
are now giving preferential trade status to their former colonies
in Africa, the Caribbean, and the Pacific regions.
</P>
<P>
The European Union plans to gradually eliminate those
preferences after the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
