<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, Turkey Settle Border Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and Turkey finally
settled their border problem, which had existed for nearly half a
century, here today with the signing of an intergovernment
agreement by the two prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Establishment of the International Border in
the Area of the Mouth of the River Rezovska and on Delimitation of
the Sea Areas between the Two Countries in the Black Sea was
signed on the first day of Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz's
two-day visit to Sofia.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov said after the signing
ceremony: "This is the first time that Bulgaria has settled a
border problem independently. This boosts our self-confidence and
dignity."
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz signaled his satisfaction over the event, saying "the
agreement protects the interests of both countries."
</P>
<P>
Also signed today were agreements on Cooperation in culture,
education and science, in mutual assistance in customs operations,
and a protocol on cooperation between the two countries' interior
ministries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on the formation of a joint working
group to seek a solution to the problem of divided families, visa
requirements and the property claims of Bulgarian and Turkish
citizens.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum on the promotion of free trade between Bulgaria
and Turkey is expected to be signed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Since assuming office, Kostov has been actively working for the
improvement of Bulgaria's neighborly ties and the overall
stability of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
