<HEADLINE> Ramos Under Fire for Failure to Smash Kidnappings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
and his government are facing a barrage of public criticism for
their failure to smash kidnapping syndicates running rampant in
the country since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Many leading local newspapers published editorials today
expressing sympathy to the victims in the latest wave of
kidnapping and prodding the Ramos administration to stem the tide
of kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
"The kidnapping must be stopped at all costs," the Manila
Chronicle stressed in its editorial. "This is the urgent call we
make to government in the face of the continuing travesty of the
law by kidnap-for-ransom gangs."
</P>
<P>
As if to mock the protest being held Tuesday by the
Chinese-Filipino community over the failure of law-enforcement
agencies to stop the rash of abductions, kidnappers struck again,
killing a son-in-law of a Chinese tycoon and abducting five
others, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
"We commiserate with the entire Chinese-Filipino community over
these senseless killings and numerous abductions that have taken
place over the past year," it said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this recent rash of abductions and senseless
killings underscores the near-total breakdown of law and order in
this country."
</P>
<P>
The editorial also appealed to Ramos to create an
anti-kidnapping task force directly responsible to himself and
thoroughly revamp the National Police to improve its capability in
fighting organized crime.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to Ramos published today by another local
newspaper, Today, more than 100 organizations, most of them
Chinese-Filipino, expressed disappointment with Ramos' failure to
restore peace and order in the country as promised in the 1992
general elections.
</P>
<P>
"Yet, with barely half a year left of your administration, the
kidnapping problem continues to terrorize the citizenry," said the
letter published as a full-page advertisement.
</P>
<P>
"Not only has the problem worsened considerably but the
kidnappers have become more and more brazen and daring, taking
victims right from inside their businesses and homes, in broad
daylight and in busy thoroughfares too," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"We have suffered long enough," they told the president, noting
that, on average, one person was being kidnapped every other day
this year.
</P>
<P>
These denunciations and appeals came as some government
officials, notably Ramos' National Security Adviser Jose Almonte,
continued to downplay the magnitude of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Almonte had accused media and certain members of the
Chinese-Filipino community of exaggerating the issue and
overreacting to it.
</P>
<P>
Presidential adviser for political affairs, Ramon Montano,
earlier even called media the "No. 1 enemy in (anti-)kidnapping
operations."
</P>
<P>
But Manila Mayor Alfredo Lim, who is known for his resolve and
success in fighting crimes, warned that investors would be
frightened away unless the peace and order situation improved at
home.
</P>
<P>
"You should first put out the fire burning your house before
asking others to come in," he told reporters when taking part in
Tuesday's protest march.  
</P>
</TEXT>
