<HEADLINE> Kohl Offers Help in Mediating Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has
offered to help break the deadlock in the Middle East peace process
during a meeting with visiting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu here late Thursday evening, Israeli diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl had not put pressure on Israel on its latest controversial
plans for a limited withdrawal from the West Bank, Israeli delegation
members told the German news agency DPA. The meeting was conducted in
a good atmosphere, they added.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders refused to make any comments before and after the
dinner meeting which was held at Kohl's chancellory residence in
Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is on a European tour which also brings him to Paris
for separate talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright
and French President Jacques Chirac on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said earlier that Netanyahu would try to seek Western
support for an Israeli plan which would involve a conditional
withdrawal of Israeli troops from six to eight percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The plan, whose details are still unknown, has already be rejected
the Palestinians as insufficent and a ploy to keep the territory under
its control.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is currently under increasing pressure from the
Western nations, with the United States in particular, to drop his
hardline policy and take concrete steps to help restart the
deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German weekly newspaper Zeit on Thursday,
the Israeli leader did not produce any signs for a major attitude
change.
</P>
<P>
He indicated in the interview that Israel would favor a second
limited withdrawal from the West Bank before the start of final-status
talks, provided that the Palestinians fulfil its anti-terrorism
obligations.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Europe to take a balanced approach to the Middle
East issues in order to play a more convincing role as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister left here for Paris Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
