<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German-Backed Forest Project in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A German-funded afforestation
project in east China's Anhui Province is proceeding smoothly,
with trees planted on 20,000 ha., or some 63 percent of the
targeted figure.
</P>
<P>
The five-year Yangtze River Shelterbelt Program, funded with a
12 million Deutschmark grant from the German Government, commenced
in 1996. The goal of the program is to reduce soil erosion by
planting trees on 31,100 ha. in the river valley.
</P>
<P>
The province invited nine foreign and 14 Chinese experts to
serve as technical advisers, and some 4,000 local people have
completed training for the program.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five percent of the water and soil conservancy, 97
percent of capital construction and 93 percent of the road
building projects have been completed, according to the program's
administration committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
