<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Rejects U.S. Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's Acting President
Rodrigo Oreamuno today rejected the allegation that organized
crime gangs were threatening the lives of U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept what the U.S. Department of State says," said
Oreamuno, who assumed the presidency of this Central American
country while President Jose Maria Figueres is visiting Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a recent U.S. State Department travel
advisory issued after a U.S. citizen and a Costa Rican farmer were
killed in a fight over a land dispute last month.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. citizens residing in the region of Pavones and Golfito
have been the target of organized gangs of squatters who have
tried to take the lands by violent means," the advisory said.
</P>
<P>
The gangs had not been punished and would continue threatening
U.S. citizens, it alleged.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Oreamuno said the allegation is an
exaggeration and, as agreed by Costa Rican political leaders and
police authorities, it does not reflect the reality of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Pavones and Golfito region is located on the southern
Pacific coast of Costa Rica, some 220 kilometers from San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
