<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Province Boosts Chemical Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Zhejiang Province hopes to
become a major chemical industrial base in east China with plans
to build five new centers.
</P>
<P>
These five centers will be in Ningbo, specializing in
petrochemicals; Jinhua and Quzhou, fluorine chemicals; Taizhou,
fine chemicals; Hangzhou, organic chemical materials and high-tech
chemicals; and Wenzhou, comprehensive utilization of alums.
</P>
<P>
The chemical industry of Zhejiang has been growing rapidly in
recent years, generating 80 billion yuan in sales last
year. Pesticide production now accounts for one-tenth of the
nation's total.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, according to the plan, the local
government every year will select 100 large and medium-size
chemical industry enterprises and help them obtain 200 million
yuan of annual sales and 10 million yuan of annual pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
In a separate plan to boost the petrochemical industry in the
province, the total output value is expected to increase by 15
percent annually in the next three years, reaching 158 billion
yuan by the end of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Leftist Rebels to Release Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The leftist rebel group, the New
People's Army (NPA), will release today a police official and an
army sergeant taken hostage after a raid on a police station in
late October this year.
</P>
<P>
The two captives will be freed somewhere in southern Luzon to a
government peace panel and the International Committee of the Red
Cross (ICRC), today's local press reports quoted a senior
government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Solicitor General Silvestre Bello, a government negotiator with
the NPA, said he and ICRC representative Paul Bonard will meet
today with NPA spokesman Gregorio Raosal and an NPA commander, who
will bring the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The release will be done between 11 a.m. and 2 p.m. today,
according to Bello.
</P>
<P>
The NPA, the military arm of the National Democratic Front
(NDF), has been persuaded to push through with the release today
despite friction caused by an alleged military offensive on a
guerrilla camp, Bello said.
</P>
<P>
The NPA has warned that it would renege on its promise to
release the two hostages if the military attack took place.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, President Fidel Ramos announced a unilateral
30-day cease-fire with the NPA to facilitate the release and the
resumption of stalled peace talks with the NDF in the Netherlands
where many NDF leaders are living in exile.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, created by the Communist Party of the Philippines in
the late 1960s, has fought the government for more than three
decades. It began its exploratory peace talks with Manila three
years ago, but the talks have been unproductive.
</P>
<P>
Military estimates put the membership of the NPA at about
8,000. 
