<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Improves Water Conservation Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
invested more than 11.7 billion yuan (1.46 billion U.S. dollars)
to improve water conservation facilities in the last five years to
help generate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province invested 3.8 billion yuan (475 million
U.S. dollars), almost quadruple the 1991 investment.
</P>
<P>
The province has built a group of major water projects such as
the Nanyi hydropower station and Shanzai Reservoir, as well as
42,700 hectares of irrigated fields. Meanwhile, the province has
taken measures to halt erosion on more than 200,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, a 1,008-kilometer sea wall had been
reinforced to withstand violent typhoons and seismic-caused sea
waves.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a flood forecasting system at a cost of 220
million yuan (27.5 million U.S. dollars) has been in operation
since the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
So far, the province's installed electrical capacity has
reached 245 million kilowatts, accounting for 10 percent of the
country's total.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has gained a total income of
6.24 billion yuan (780 million U.S. dollars) from the water
conservation industry since the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The province also has invested 21 million yuan in scientific
research on water conservation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
