<HEADLINE> Italian Wins Men's Downhill Season-opening Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Kristian Ghedina of Italy
won the season-opening men's World Cup downhill race at Beaver
Creek, Colorado, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the eighth career victory for Ghedina, who beat Jean-Luc
Cretier of France and Lasse Kjus of Norway to the second and third
places in the race respectively.
</P>
<P>
Cretier, who was 22-hundredths of a second behind Ghedina, tied
his career-best World Cup finish he set in 1994 in Chemonix,
France.
</P>
<P>
Cretier had finished no better than 12th, and that in a super
giant slalom event, in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Kjus, the 1996 overall World Cup champion, had to be settled
for the third place as he finished 24-hundredths of a second
behind Ghedina. 
</P>
