<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Humanitarian Concerns, Self-Defense Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The general principle of solving
the landmine problem should be one that takes balanced account of
both humanitarian concerns and the legitimate military needs of
sovereign states for self-defense, a senior Chinese official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ongoing Ottawa landmine conference, Zha Peixin,
head of the Chinese Observer Delegation, stressed that countries
differ in national conditions and defense needs.
</P>
<P>
"For many countries, especially those lacking advanced
defensive weapons, anti-personnel landmines (APLs) remain an
effective means of self-defense. Moreover, the issue of national
security is in itself an important aspect of humanitarianism," Zha
said.
</P>
<P>
"Before an alternative of APLs is found, the Chinese army must
reserve the right to use APLs on its own soil so as to form
defense capability.
</P>
<P>
"The sole purpose of this reservation lies in safeguarding
national unity and territorial integrity of the country and
ensuring the peaceful life of the Chinese people," the official
noted.
</P>
<P>
It is also in conformity with the right of self-defense
enshrined in the UN Charter and will not constitute a threat to
civilians of any country, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has all along attached great importance to humanitarian
concerns over landmine problems, favored humanitarian efforts of
the international community aimed at preventing casualties of
innocent civilians by the Plyndmines.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that strengthening restrictions on use and
banning abusive use of landmines constitute one of the important
aspects of reduction and total elimination of landmine casualties
to civilians," Zha told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government calls for all states to join, ratify and
observe the amended Landmine Protocol of the CCW.
</P>
<P>
Zha said removal of landmines laid in the past is another
important aspect in addressing the indiscriminate effect of
landmine on civilians and represents "the most urgent problem"
faced by the international community.
</P>
<P>
"China will continue to actively take part in international
efforts at mine clearance," he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, China is studying and mapping out plans to assist
countries suffering from landmine problems in mine-clearance
training, technology and equipment, including making contributions
to the international fund on mine clearance, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AFC Supports HKFA in Operating the Game: AFC President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- "We will give all the support
to Mr. Timothy Fok Tsun-ting in running the Hong Kong Football
Association (HKFA) to uphold the old glory," Sultan Ahmad Shah,
president of the Asian Football Confederation (AFC), said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"HKFA is a family member of the Asian football and FIFA has
reconfirmed its status," Shah said.
</P>
<P>
The AFC chief was speaking at a tea reception given in his
honor by the HKFA here today.
</P>
<P>
Shah and his entourage, who arrived here on Wednesday, are
paying an unofficial visit here.
</P>
<P>
During his speech at today's reception, Sultan Shah recalled
that HKFA, as one of AFC's 12 founding members in 1954, was one of
the Asian football powers during the 1950s and 1960s and has been
playing an active role in Asian football.
</P>
<P>
He said that other Asian teams had progressed faster than Hong
Kong and Asia has so improved that it has "reached a respectable
level", with four teams qualified this year for the 1998 World Cup
finals in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"As AFC president, I'm very proud to have four teams in the
World Cup finals and I'm confident that Japan, South Korea, Iran
and Saudi Arabia who have qualified could carry the Asian flag
with dignity and honor," he continued.
</P>
<P>
He urged the HKFA to further their efforts to improve their
standard of play, hoping more games with teams from China's inland
areas will help Hong Kong teams improve faster.
</P>
<P>
Fok admitted that lack of facilities, among others, is a
problem for Hong Kong football and, "We'd had to have our own
stars," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
