<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a more
than 5-year intraday high against the Japanese yen Thursday after
Japan released disappointing economic data.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar settled at 129.39 yen, up
from 128.78 late Wednesday. The dollar hit an intraday high of
129.74 against the yen, not seen since May 28, 1992, when the
dollar reached 130.25.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7715 marks, down
slightly from 1.7720.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government announced Thursday that the country's
gross domestic product in the July-September quarter grew an
inflation-adjusted 0.8 percent, from the April-June period.
Analysts had forecast growth of about 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The British pound also fell against the dollar as the Bank of
England declined to raise interest rates. The British pound was
quoted at 1.6669 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6829 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4318 Swiss francs, up from 1.4301; 5.9260 French
francs, down from 5.9315; 1,736.70 Italian lire, up from 1,736; and
1.4299 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4191. 
</P>
</TEXT>
