<HEADLINE> SPD Vows to Set New Course for Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANNOVER, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD) concluded here today a three-day
party congress by vowing to replace Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
coalition government in next year's general elections and set
Germany on a new course.
</P>
<P>
"We want to win the next general elections so as to push
through a new policy in Germany," said SPD party leader and a
possible challenger to Kohl, Oskar Lafontaine, at the end of the
congress.
</P>
<P>
The Thursday meeting, however, was highlighted by an policy
speech delivered by the SPD premier of the Lower Saxony state,
Gerhard Schroeder, who is rivaling with Lafontaine to be the
party's formal chancellor candidate for the elections due in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to the keynote speech made by Lafontaine on
Monday calling for more state role to run economy, Schroeder today
suggested to slash state regulations and bureaucracy to help cure
the country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who has a pro-business and modernizer image,
received a boost today when his economic concept was adopted by a
large majority by the SPD delegates in Hannover.
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called "Innovations for Germany" concept, the SPD
calls for more investment in education and research to boost
Germany's future competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
As its main remedies to cut the country's record high
unemployment, the SPD calls for an economic expansion policy, tax
cuts, as well as more flexible working hours and labour contracts.
</P>
<P>
Despite the differences in ideas, Lafontaine and Schroeder have
managed to avoid public rifts at the party congress and pledged to
join force to bring their party back to power after 15 years in
opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We will deliver an excellent team play," said Schroeder at the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
