<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Renew Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today decided to renew Iraqi Oil-for-food plan
for another period of six months effective from December 5, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The current program expires on Friday and is aimed to
alleviate the impact of UN trade sanctions on Iraq which has been
in place since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reaffirmed the commitment of all member
States to the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its willingness to find ways of
improving the implementation of the humanitarian program and
to take actions over additional resources as needed to meet the
priority humanitarian requirement of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the resolution 986 of the United Nations
adopted in April, 1995, Iraq is allowed to sell 2 billion U.S.
dollars worth of oil every six months to buy humanitarian goods
for its people. But the oil-for-food plan was not implemented
until last December.
</P>
<P>
Till now, Iraq has implemented two phases of oil-for-food
plan.  
</P>
