<HEADLINE> Tanzanian School Dropouts High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The 15 percent rate of
primary school leavers joining secondary schools in Tanzania is a
clear indication that school completion rates are low and
dropouts are high, "The Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, citing a report by the United Nations
Development Program, said the east African country continues
facing severe problems in the education sector.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP Development Cooperation Report for Tanzania for 1996,
which was released on Wednesday in Dar es Salaam, says that
transition rate of 15 percent from primary to secondary education
was very low in comparison with ratios of secondary education
enrollment in other sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
"The quality of education at all levels has yet to improve due
to insufficient supply of qualified teachers, classrooms and
education materials," the report notes.
</P>
<P>
The report points out that insufficient funding for
educational activities and inadequate remuneration of teachers
have also contributed to the generally poor quality of education.
</P>
