<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Talks Should Achieve Breakthrough: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
special envoy for the Middle East peace process said here today
that the Palestinians and Israelis should achieve breakthrough in
their peace talks before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Viktor Posuvalyuk, the Russian envoy, made the remark while
briefing Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan on the outcome of his
present regional tour which is part of Russia's efforts to put the
peace process back on track, Jordan's official news agency Petra
reported.
</P>
<P>
A solution for the problem between the Palestinians and
Israelis should be found before the new year, the agency quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, details of the special envoy's idea have not been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk said that Russia believed that the two sides were
committed to peace but the problem was that each side had its own
conditions and demands.
</P>
<P>
Russia held that the door between the Palestinians and Israelis
was closed, but there were windows from which the mediators could
enter to help overcome the deadlock between the two sides, said
the special envoy who arrived here Wednesday from Israel.
</P>
<P>
Russia would continue its efforts to help resume talks
between Israel and the Arab states, said Posuvalyuk who earlier
held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Tel
Aviv and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat in the West Bank
city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Russia's willingness to cooperate with the United
States, the European Union and all the concerned parties in the
region to push the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Hassan reiterated Jordan's support for
the Palestinian demand that Israel carry out all its obligations
under the interim accords.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at a press conference after meeting Netanyahu and
Arafat, Posuvalyuk said that all sides should strictly abide by
all the signed peace accords and not take any unilateral moves
that would influence the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk was named special envoy in heel of Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov's visit to the region in November.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected a recent Israeli cabinet
decision to implement only a limited one-phase redeployment to
withdraw from 6-8 percent of the West Bank. Jordan supported the
rejection.
</P>
<P>
The signed Palestinian-Israeli interim accords stipulate
that Israeli redeployment from 90 percent of the West Bank be
implemented in a three-phase withdrawal to be finished by
mid-1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
