<HEADLINE> Somali Negotiators Agree on Federal Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The participants of the
on-going Somali negotiations in Cairo have agreed upon the need
for a national reconciliation conference and the establishment of
a government based on federal system with regional autonomy.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here today by Ismail Warsame, Executive
Assistant to the Somali National Salvation Council (SNSC).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local press, he said the Cairo
negotiation which is being attended by delegates of SNSC and
Hussein Aideed's faction, has yet other crucial issues to
resolve.
</P>
<P>
He added, the venue of the reconciliation conference,
representation at the conference and the leaving of Hussein
Aideed's militia from occupied regions around Mogadishu are among
the issues yet to be resolved at the negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Warsame stressed that "for the national reconciliation
conference to succeed, it is absolutely necessary for Hussein
Aideed's militia to leave those places."
</P>
<P>
The venue of the national reconciliation conference, which is
decided by SNSC at the Sodere peace conference to be at Bossasso,
is being discussed at the Cairo negotiation between SNSC and
Hussein Aideed's group, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, some 12 committees comprising more than 200 members
are working hard in Bossasso for the reconciliation conference to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement reached by the negotiation parties
in Cairo, they have approved the establishment of a three-year
period transitional government.
</P>
<P>
A presidential council composed of 13 members elected by the
National Reconciliation Conference will be established. The
members of the presidential council will on their part elect a
president by a simple majority vote. The date of the
reconciliation conference will be decided following the
conclusion of the Cairo negotiations. 
</P>
