<HEADLINE> Moi to Get 40 Percent of Vote: Opinion Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The results of an opinion poll
showed that the incumbent President Daniel arap Moi will capture
40.8 percent of the vote in the December 29 General Election.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted by the Institute for Education in Democracy
(IED) predicted that Moi will get at least 25 percent of the vote
in seven of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Constitution provides that the winning presidential
candidate must gather at least 25 percent of the vote in at least
five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here today by IED said that Mwai Kibaki,
Chairman of the opposition Democratic Party of Kenya, will rank
second with 13.7 percent and opposition Social Democratic Party
Chairman Charity Ngilu will finish third with 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first multi-party elections held in 1992, Moi garnered
35.8 percent of the vote with Kenneth Matiba getting 26.4 percent
and Kibaki 20.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Matiba is not a candidate this year as he refused to register
as a voter, and he has called for a boycott against the coming
General Election.
</P>
<P>
The poll indicated that 11 percent of those questioned were
undecided about whom to vote for.
</P>
<P>
The IED pointed out that "with the campaigns kicking off, the
results could change substantially."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the poll was conducted on November 29
and 30, and involved 1,500 households from 42 out of the 210
constituencies in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
IED which receives official funds from the U.S., Britain and
Scandinavian countries is one of the most established Kenyan
non-governmental organizations in the democracy field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
