<HEADLINE> U.S. to Shift Foreign Policy on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States' foreign
policy on Africa is set to shift from that of dictating on how
the continent's leaders should run their countries to that of
forging partnerships, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for
African Affairs Susan Rice said today.
</P>
<P>
"In the past there was too much finger waving diplomacy with
the U.S. telling African governments on what to do," said Rice.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to listen and hear from the leadership on what
role the U.S. can play in Africa. The U.S. can play a
constructive role when it is desired by the governments of the
regions," she said.
</P>
<P>
She was fielding questions from journalists and interested
groups from Harare, Kampala and Addis Ababa via satellite ahead
of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit to seven
African countries beginning December 8, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
She said the U.S. was "very encouraged" by the trend whereby
African leaders now took the primary responsibility of solving
their own problems. Meanwhile, Rice expressed frustration that
reconciliation was still to be achieved in war-torn Somalia,
saying solution to the crisis in the Horn of Africa country
rested squarely with the Somalis themselves.
</P>
<P>
Albright's trip will focus on advancing U.S. interests in the
Great Lakes region, developing partnership with a new generation
of African leaders and reaching out directly to people,
particularly the youth who will take Africa into the 21st
century, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported. 
</P>
