<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptians Embrace High-Tech at Mideast Biggest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is trying to take the
advantage of the opportunity to develop its information technology
(IT) as the largest IT show in the Arab world, Cairo Telecomp '97,
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
With over 180 companies from 25 Arab, European, American and
Asian countries and regions, the list of exhibitors at the show
reads like a "Who is Who" of the international telecommunications
and IT community.
</P>
<P>
In its second year, the International Telecom, IT, Satellite
and Broadcasting Technology Trade Fair for the Arab-North Africa,
has established itself as an indispensable event for the regional
market, Martin Marz, managing director of the fair, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
On the show grounds, as computer professionals took advantage
of a free access to the Internet in the conference hall, curious
visitors were attracted to the eye-catching stands of some
international high-tech heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
Arianespace, the world's first space transportation company
based in Europe, placed a model of the NILESAT, Egypt's first
satellite due to be launched early next year, in the center of a
flood-lit platform in the Cairo International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
The French-made NILESAT, a 158-million-U.S. dollar project,
will be able to transmit 12 channels, with each airing six
programs simultaneously through digital technology.
</P>
<P>
Experts told Xinhua that Egypt remains one of the world's last
large, untapped cellular markets. The telecommunications services
in Egypt are controlled by the sole telecommunications authority
TelecomEgypt.
</P>
<P>
The number of telephone lines in Egypt have been growing by 9.4
percent to reach 4,780,000 while each 100 subscribers own 7.9
lines in 1997, compared with 1.2 in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's personal computer market has grown at the world's
fastest rate for the second year in a row, according to the
International Data Corp., a leading industry monitor and
consultant.
</P>
<P>
Egypt saw shipment of nearly 84,000 units in 1996, registering
a growth of 46 percent than that of the previous year. The
nation's number of installed units reached 311,886 in the same
year, representing a growth rate of 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, out of the 62 million population, only 48,000
Egyptians use the pager installed since 1990, and mobiles
introduced here 13 months ago remain a pricey novelty.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the under-development of Egypt's telecommunications
industry, Egyptian Minister of Transport and Communications
Soliman Metwalli Soliman said at today's opening ceremony that
Arab and North African countries have to carve out a place for
themselves in the IT market.
</P>
<P>
The importance of information can never be overestimated as it
has now taken on the function of a fourth productive factor in
addition to the classic productive factors of labor, soil and
capital, said Marz.
</P>
<P>
In parallel to four days of crowds of visitors at the booths,
fertile talks, negotiations and seminars will be held.
</P>
<P>
Under the slogan "Middle East through Communication," ministers
of Algeria, Egypt, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, and Syria, will attend
various workshops and symposiums during the four-day fair, in a
bid to boost the Arab telecommunications industry whose revenues
account for 1.2 percent of the world total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
