<HEADLINE> Ministerial Panel Fails Again to Agree on Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The ministerial committee
responsible for formulating Israel's second redeployment in West
Bank and guidelines on the permanent talks with the Palestinians
held second meeting here today, but again failed to reach an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
before his departure for an European tour, which will take him to
Germany and France for a series of important meetings with
European leaders to discuss the peace process.
</P>
<P>
All other committee members, including Foreign Minister David
Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted an aide to one of the ministers as saying
that the committee held "serious deliberations" over mapping the
extent of another redeployment and the guidelines for impending
final-status talks with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The aide disclosed that the committee was equally divided
between Netanyahu and Sharon, who favored the establishment of an
expansive security zone, and Levy and Mordechai, who insisted that
the security zone could be much smaller. Levy and Mordechai
reportedly said that Israel should go forward with the second
redeployment in order to win diplomatic points.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during an inspection tour to the Eretz Crossing
between Israel and Gaza Strip, Mordechai said Israel must carry
out the second redeployment because it will open the way for the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied a power struggle within the ministerial
panel over the further redeployment, adding he expected an
agreement to be reached during Sunday's session. He also stressed
that there was no pressure from the United States on Israel over
the redeployment issue, adding that all decisions will be based on
Israel's best interests.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial panel is to meet against next week upon
Netanyahu's return from his current visits to Germany and France in
a bid to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu flied to the German capital of Bonn late this
afternoon for talks with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. He then
will travel to Paris Friday to hold meetings with United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and French President Jacques
Chirac to discuss the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to push for Israel's carrying out the
delayed second redeployment in the West Bank and its agreement to
a time-out of Israeli settlements so to advance the stalemated
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israeli state television Channel I Wednesday,
Levy said he thought that his proposal for keeping the settlement
activities to a minimal level could satisfy the demand for a
time-out of settlement expansion as put forward by Albright.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department said Wednesday that Washington was
not satisfied with the Israeli-set 6-8 percent of further
redeployment as reported by the media, while saying the PNA's
hope for getting most of the West Bank in the final settlement was
also unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is trying to bridging the huge gap between the two
sides in order to achieve progress in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said the Netanyahu-Albright talks, the second held
in Europe for the past weeks, would likely have impact on the
much-expected summit between Netanyahu and U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been trying hard to arrange this summit during
Netanyahu's visit to the U.S. last month, but Clinton snubbed the
Israeli leader to express his dissatisfaction with his handling of
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
