<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Second Annual Loan for Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today announced the approval of the second annual loan
for Tanzania, an equivalent to 97 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to support Tanzania's economic
program for 1997/98. The initial amount of some 69.8 million
dollars has been increased by about 27.17 million dollars to
assist the eastern African nation in dealing with the effect of
drought.
</P>
<P>
The loan is made available in two equal semiannual
installments, the first of which can be disbursed on December 19,
this year.
</P>
<P>
The key macroeconomic objectives of the 1997/98 program include
achieving a real GDP growth rate of 4.7 percent, reducing the
inflation rate to no more than 13 percent and limiting the external
current account deficit to some 14.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania joined the IMF in September, 1962. Its quota is about
200 million dollars equivalent and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 204 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
