<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that the Egyptian-Qatari ties remain good,
adding that the two countries enjoy a permanent friendship.
</P>
<P>
"Egyptian-Qatari ties are good at present, were good in the
past and will remain good in the future," Moussa told reporters,
apparently playing down the recent tense relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
"What happened was just an exception to that rule," he added,
describing Wednesday's talks in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, between
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin
Khalifa al-Thani as "good."
</P>
<P>
Mediated by Saudi Arabia, Egypt and Qatar Wednesday patched
up their disputes during the meeting between the leaders of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Arab League Secretary-General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid today voiced his delight over success of Saudi
Arabia's mediation to dispel the cloud that enveloped the Arab
giant and the small Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
"I hope such way of settling inter-misunderstandings would be
applied all along," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Qatari relations deteriorated in October when Egypt
was ready to boycott the fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic conference which was held in the Qatari capital of Doha
last month.
</P>
<P>
Qatar responded with a ban on the entry of nationals of Egypt
alongside other nine countries as a security precaution for the
Doha conference, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to their row were Qatar's charges that Egypt had
plotted the 1996 coup attempt to overthrow the Gulf sheikdom's
emir. Egypt rejected the charges and demanded for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
Signals for solving the crisis came to the fore Monday as their
war of words on the media eased amid intensive mediation by Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The reconciliation bids involved messages sent by Saudi King
Fahd to the leaders of Egypt and Qatar and visits by their foreign
ministers to Riyadh before Wednesday's summit. 
</P>
