<HEADLINE> Poll Finds More American Youth Accept "Separate but </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- More young people in the
United States have come to see nothing wrong with the races
keeping to themselves as long as they are not discriminated
against, said a poll released Wednesday by MTV, the youth-oriented
cable network.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 54 percent of young people characterize
race relations as "good," compared with 42 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But young people seem increasingly accepting of the "separate
but equal" concept -- the phrase at the heart of the civil rights
dispute that poses the question whether separate facilities can
ever be equal.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, 41 percent of youth said it was "OK if the races are
basically separate from one another in our country as long as
everyone has equal opportunities." That figure rose to 68 percent
in the 1997 survey.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of those who disagree with the "separate but
equal" philosophy fell from 57 percent in 1991 to 31 percent
today.
</P>
<P>
"What young people are saying in this poll, and what our
audience tells us, is that there is still much work to be done,"
said Judy McGrath, MTV President. "This is no time for
complacency."
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted from September 17-30 by GarinHartYang
Research, sampled more than 750 people aged 15-24. The margin of
error is plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Car Insurers to Pay NHS Crash Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The British government plans to
force insurance companies to be charged for the cost of National
Health Service (NHS) treatment for road crash victims, said local
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Health Secretary Frank Dobson will unveil
the plan today and he will also order hospital chiefs to claw back
millions of pounds from the cost of treating crash victims over
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Although the power to claim back care costs from insurers has
been in place since the 1930s, it has not been widely used and the
NHS has been put off claiming by time-consuming procedures.
</P>
<P>
That is why the government will announce a change in the law to
ensure insurance firms automatically pay up.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, insurance firms covering a driver who caused an
accident will pay up to 3,000 pounds (5,040 US dollars) for
hospital care and 300 pounds for outpatient treatment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, insurers will also be asked to meet the cost of an
ambulance sent to the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 300,000 people are treated by the
NHS each year for car crash injuries at a cost of around 440
million pounds (739.2 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to save around 100 million pounds (168
million US dollars) a year, but at the same time, will increase
car insurance premiums for the country's 23 million motorists by
up to 20 pounds per annum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971205.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Financial Crisis Will Be Over Soon, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis
will be over soon with the joint efforts of the international
world and governments of Asian countries, officials and economists
asserted here today.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar hosted here today by the Asia Society, a
non-governmental organization engaged in promoting U.S.-Asian
relationship, U.S. trade officials and economists shared their
views on the latest development of the financial market in
Southeast Asia and its impact on trade, financial and investment
issues globally.
</P>
<P>
The guest speakers, including John Wolf, U.S. Coordinator for
APEC, and Harinder Kohli, Senior Operations Advisor from the World
Bank, indicated again the need for Asian countries to open their
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Robert Denham, Chairman and CEO of the Salomon, Inc., turned
down the idea that speculators played a big role in the Asian
crisis. "What weighs more is the economic fundamentals," he said,
adding that bad loans and poor management of banks and security
institutions are very obvious problems.
</P>
<P>
China more or less survived the crisis this time, but for a
long-term protection, it should quicken the steps of opening its
financial market, according to Malcolm Binks, Senior Vice
President of the International Department of Merrill Lynch, a
leading securities firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
Binks said that Hong Kong has successfully overcome the crisis
with its pegging system between the H.K. dollar and U.S. dollar.
The system will continue to work in a short term. But he said it
is expensive for Hong Kong to stick to the system in a long term,
especially when its neighbors have devaluated their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Binks also said that he believed the financial crisis in Asia
will be over soon, because of the pressure of investors and
measures taken by the governments. But the medicine and dosage
will be different for the ailment of different countries,
according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
The speakers also agreed that Asia's financial woes will not
affect too much on the still-strong U.S. economy. But according to
the latest surveys of the U.S. Federal Reserve, U.S. manufacturers
were starting to feel the impact of the Asian Crisis. Sales to the
region slowed a bit, and Asian competitors were cutting prices on
imports to the U.S., widening the trade gap.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
