<HEADLINE> France, Germany Determined to Remain in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany today affirmed
their determination to maintain their military presence in Bosnia
after June 1998, when the Stabilization Force (SFOR) ends its
mission.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and his French counterpart
Hubert Vedrine, who made a visit to Sarajevo today, said that a
military guarantee for the peace process in Bosnia would be
necessary after the date, according reports from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel and Vedrine met with the three members of the Bosnian
presidency, Alija Izetbegovic, Kresimir Zubak and Momcilo
Krajisnik, as well as the president of Republika Srpska, Biljan
Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
The visit by the two ministers to Bosnia came before the
holding of the meeting in Bonn on December 9-10 by members of the
follow-up committee of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Defense Minister Alain Richard said today
that the United States government should not use the U.S. Congress
as "an alibi" in the discussion about the post-SFOR period in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Radio-Television Luxembourg (RTL),
Richard also said that he is convinced the United States will
maintain its presence in Bosnia after June 1998, when the SFOR
completes its mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
