<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spells out Position on Security Council Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China reiterated today
that the enlargement of the U.N. Security Council should follow
the principle of equitable geographical distribution and ensure a
proper balance between the developing and developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to the United Nations Qin Huasun told the
52nd Session of U.N. General Assembly that the international
community needs to be vigilant against the proposal for
admitting some countries into the Security Council in a "quick
fix" manner "through the backdoor".
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the fact that although the so-called quick fix
proposal has been turned down, a small number of countries are
still using such argument as "to view the question practically and
take into full consideration of the actual situation in various
different regions" as an excuse to practice double standards and
discriminate against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The hard-won understanding about the sufficient representation
of developing countries in the Security Council should be the
basis and prerequisite for future reform of the Council, he said,
noting that "any reform plan that deviates from this common
understanding will not be feasible."
</P>
<P>
Attaching importance to the transparency of the Council's work,
Qin said China has always worked actively in this regard.
</P>
<P>
China paid much attention to improving the efficiency of the
work of the Council when assuming the presidency of the Council
in November, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
China properly handled many urgent issues while trying hard to
enhance the transparency by briefing non-Council members the same
day when consultations were held.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China is in favor of the Council's enlargement, but it
maintains that full and patient discussions and consultations are
needed.
</P>
<P>
"Any action to set a deadline to the reform or force a vote on
certain proposal in the General Assembly when conditions are not
yet ripe will bring about serious consequences," he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
