<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Albright Discuss Mideast Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has talked with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the
Middle East peace process before she meets with Israeli and
Palestinian leaders in Europe on the weekend, The White House said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that
Clinton and Albright agreed that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat should "focus
intently on the immediate issues" that the United States had put
forward.
</P>
<P>
The issues include security cooperation, Israeli military
redeployments, a "time-out" in construction of Jewish
settlements and an "accelerated timing for negotiating final
status issues".
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Netanyahu and Arafat "know that that's the
agenda, and they can well expect the secretary to come prepared
to press those particular issues with determination."
</P>
<P>
Albright plans to meet Netanyahu in Paris on Friday and
Arafat in Geneva on Saturday on her way to a week-long trip to
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
