<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Russia's Offer to Reduce Forces on Baltic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States welcomed
Russia's offer to reduce military forces on its borders with the
Baltic states, a State Department spokesman announced today.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't had an opportunity to study the proposals but we've
had a cursory look at them," said State Department spokesman James
Rubin when referring to a statement by Russian President Boris
Yeltsin during a current visit to Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that Russia would unilaterally cut its ground and
naval forces by 40 percent in just over a year while his aides
said this would apply to northern Russia bordering the Baltic
states.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome efforts by all nations in the region to foster
stability and enhance regional cooperation," Rubin told a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We also note that Russia previously proposed measures designed
for further cooperation among northern European states.... We
support such cooperation and are willing to participate actively
in it," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin stressed that the "inherent right of the Baltic
states to choose the means to ensure their own security" should be
respected.
</P>
<P>
The Baltic states, Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, regained
their independence in 1991 from the former Soviet Union. They are
now applying for memberships of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Russia opposes any expansion of NATO to the Baltic states while
the U.S. says Russia has no veto over which east European country
can join the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
